is not dangerous. The following variation is very natural:} h6 10. Bh4 Rb8 11.
Kh1 Be7 12. Rb1 d6 13. Qe2 Be6 14. b3 Nd7 15. Bg3 Nc5 16. Bc4 Qa5 17. Bxe6 Nxe6
$11 {and Black is fine.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. f4 {The only active idea for White,
but Black stays solid anyway.} d6 10. Kh1 (10. fxe5 {can be met by} Ng4 $1 {
[%cal Gg4e5] when Black achieves a strong post for the knight on e5, since} 11.
exd6 $4 Bxd6 $19 {is obviously hopeless for White.}) 10... exf4 11. Bxf4 Be6 {
[%csl Yc5,Ye5][%cal Gf6d7] Black's next idea is the typical maneuver Nd7, with
a strong regrouping. White can avoid this plan by means of} 12. e5 {but after}
dxe5 13. Bxe5 Nd7 14. Bd4 g6 $11 {[%cal Ge7c5,Gd7c5] Black's position seems
totally fine.}) ({Other continuations also don't pose problems for Black, for
example:} 7. Qf3 Be7 8. Bc4 O-O 9. O-O d6 10. h3 h6 11. Be3 Be6 12. Bb3 d5 $15)
({Or} 7. a3 Bc5 8. Bc4 O-O 9. O-O Bd4 10. Qf3 d6 11. h3 Be6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 $15 {
in both cases, Black has a comfortable game.}) 7... Bb4 {Putting pressure in
the centre.} (7... Bc5 {and}) (7... Be7 {are also playable.}) 8. O-O (8. Bg5 $6
{seems imprecise as after} h6 {White has to part with the bishop pair.} 9. Bxf6
(9. Bh4 $2 {is bad in view of} g5 10. Bg3 Nxe4 11. Bxe5 Qe7 $1 {when even
after the best continuation} 12. Qd4 f6 13. Qxe4 Qxe5 14. Qxe5+ fxe5 $17 {
[%csl Gb4,Gc8][%cal Yd7d5] Black keeps a big advantage.}) 9... Qxf6 10. O-O O-O
{and Black has a pleasant game, with the bishop pair and nice chances in the
centre.}) ({Another interesting line is} 8. Qf3 O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11.
Qxf6 gxf6 12. O-O-O {Now Black has a nice idea:} f5 $1 {with strong play in
the centre, for example:} 13. f3 (13. exf5 $2 d5 14. Bd3 e4 $17) 13... Kg7 14.
exf5 d5 15. Bd3 h5 16. g4 hxg4 17. fxg4 e4 18. Be2 Rh8 19. h4 Be7 20. h5 Kh6
$17 {Despite being a pawn down, it's Black who has a clear advantage here.})
8... O-O ({In case of} 8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 Nxe4 10. Ba3 $5 $44 {White gets
decent compensation for the pawn.}) 9. Bg5 ({In case of} 9. Qd3 {Black has the
active reaction} d5 10. exd5 Bxc3 11. Qxc3 cxd5 {with a comfortable position,
for example:} 12. Bd3 (12. Rd1 $2 {is a serious mistake:} Bg4 $1 13. f3 Rc8 $19
{and Black is already winning.}) 12... Re8 13. Re1 d4 14. Qc5 e4 15. Bb5 Bd7
16. Bxd7 Qxd7 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8,Yd4d3] when Black already has an easier game.})
9... h6 10. Bh4 (10. Bxf6 Qxf6 {is simply pleasant for Black, as we've seen in
similar positions.}) 10... g5 $5 {I like this move, neutralizing the pin and
putting the dark-squared bishop out of play for a while.} 11. Bg3 Qe7 ({
Black can also force some imbalance with} 11... Bxc3 $5 {The position after}
12. bxc3 Qe7 13. Qd3 d6 14. Rad1 Rd8 15. f3 $11 {seems dynamically balanced.})
12. Qd3 ({Another possible continuation is} 12. Qe2 d6 13. Rad1 Rd8 14. f3 Rb8
15. Bf2 Nh5 $36 {with some initiative for Black.}) 12... Rd8 13. Rad1 d6 14. f3
