1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Nf3 {This retreat was
played by some strong players, but it allows Black to get a good game very
easily by simple active play.} Bb4 7. Bc4 {The best option according to the
engine. Also, I remember that a long time ago someone tried to convince me
this line was a worth option for White, though honestly I didn't buy it.} (7.
Bd3 {is more passive.} O-O 8. O-O (8. Bd2 {avoids doubling pawns on the c-file.
On the other hand, Black takes advantage of the lead in development to achieve
a serious advantage with} d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Bxb4 Nxb4 {when
even further simplifications don't solve White's problems, for instance:} 12.
a3 Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3 Qc6 14. Qe2 Bg4 $17) {Black has a typical positional
operation now:} 8... Bxc3 $1 9. bxc3 h6 $1 {avoiding Bg5. Black's next plan is
simple: we want to develop pressure against the doubled pawns on the c-file,
in style of Nimzo positions. A logical variation could be} 10. h3 d6 11. Be3
Be6 12. Nd2 Rc8 13. c4 b6 $15 {[%csl Rc2,Rc4][%cal Gc6a5,Gf6d7,Gd7c5] Black
has a pleasant position and can increase the pressure by means of typical
maneuvers like Na5, Nd7-c5 etc.}) (7. Bg5 {leads to a similar path after} h6 8.
Bxf6 Bxc3+ $1 9. bxc3 Qxf6 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3] when the exchange of one more pair
of pieces has only helped Black.} 10. Bc4 d6 11. Qd3 ({Black is also better
after} 11. O-O Bg4 12. Be2 O-O 13. Nd2 Be6 14. Nc4 Rfd8 15. Ne3 Rac8 $17 {
[%cal Gc6a5]}) 11... O-O 12. O-O b6 13. Rfd1 Na5 $1 14. Bd5 ({Or} 14. Bb3 Rd8
$17 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8]}) 14... Bb7 15. Bb3 Rfd8 $17 {[%cal Ga8c8] Black has
an obvious advantage.}) (7. Bd2 $2 {is a blunder. White simply loses a pawn in
a long forced line:} Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Nxe4 9. Nxe5 (9. Bxe5 $2 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Qa5+
$19 {is the tactical point.}) 9... Nxc3 10. Nxc6 Nxd1 11. Nxd8 Nxb2 12. Nxb7
Bxb7 13. Rb1 Bxg2 $1 14. Bxg2 Rb8 $17) 7... O-O 8. O-O (8. Bg5 {doesn't
improves White's chances.} h6 9. Bh4 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 d6 11. O-O Qe7 12. Qd3 Rd8
13. Rad1 Be6 $15 {The pin is simply harmless and Black keeps developing the
pressure on the c-file without problems.}) 8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 d6 ({In case of} 
9... Nxe4 {White can play} 10. Ba3 d6 11. Re1 Ng5 12. Bd5 $11 {when Black
probably will return the pawn.}) 10. Ba3 {The most active.} (10. Qd3 {is also
natural, but in this case Black achieves a good development by means of} Re8
11. Rd1 Be6 12. Bg5 Rc8 {White is able to keep the balance here with} 13. Bb5
h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxd6 {despite even here, after} a6 16. Be2 (16. Bxc6 $2
Rxc6 17. Qxe5 Qxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxc3 $17 {is already better for Black.}) 16... Red8
17. Qa3 Rc7 18. Rxd8+ Qxd8 $11 {Black is fine. White's pawn advantage has no
value in practice, and the pressure on the c-file is still annoying.}) 10...
Na5 $1 {Black manages to solve all the opening problems thanks to this move.}
11. Bb3 ({But not} 11. Bd3 $2 Qc7 $17 {and Black consolidates a big advantage.}
) 11... Nxe4 12. Re1 Bf5 {Black is about to consolidate his position, but
White manages to equalize with correct play:} 13. Qd5 $1 (13. Qd3 {is a bit
tricky in view of} Re8 $1 {when White needs to be more precise to avoid
problems.} 14. Bd5 (14. Rxe4 $2 Nxb3 15. axb3 d5 $19 {is the trap.}) 14... Nf6
$1 15. Qxf5 Nxd5 16. Rad1 Qf6 17. Qxf6 Nxf6 18. Bxd6 e4 19. Nd4 Nc4 $11 {
White should be ok with correct play here, but I prefer Black's chances a
little bit.}) 13... Nxc3 14. Qxd6 {Many exchanges take place now and result in
an equal ending:} Re8 15. Rxe5 Qxd6 16. Bxd6 Nxb3 17. cxb3 Rxe5 18. Bxe5 Rc8
$11 *

