1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Nb3 {This retreat
doesn't seem objectively better than 6.Nf3, but it can be found in games of
Ivanchuk, Gelfand, Jobava and other strong players.} Bb4 7. Bd2 {This is not
the most popular reply, but I think it is the most solid for White.} (7. Bd3 {
is the most played, but the natural} d5 {gives a pleasant position for Black.}
8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Bd2 Nxc3 10. bxc3 ({Inferior is} 10. Bxc3 $6 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 O-O
12. O-O Qc7 $15 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3][%cal Yf7f5] with an obvious advantage for
Black, as the exchange of dark-squared bishops makes the c3-pawn weaker and
reduces White's chances of active play.}) 10... Be7 11. Qh5 $5 {Played by
Jobava, aims to provoke at least one concession on Black's camp.} ({Normal
play leads to an advantage for Black:} 11. O-O O-O 12. f4 f5 13. fxe5 Nxe5 14.
Be2 ({In case of} 14. Qe2 Nxd3 15. cxd3 b6 $17 {the bishop pair keeps a
serious advantage for Black.}) 14... Bf6 15. Be3 g6 $15 {In practice looks
like Black is up a pawn here, White has to fight to equalize.}) 11... g6 12.
Qe2 (12. Qh6 {doesn't really prevent Black from castling:} Bf8 13. Qe3 Bg7 14.
Qc5 Qc7 15. O-O b6 16. Qa3 Ne7 $1 $15 {[%cal Ge8g8] and Black is finally able
to castle.}) 12... O-O 13. h4 $6 {Jobava,B (2669)-Bykhovsky,A (2459) EU-ch
10th Budva 2009 (3) 1-0 an attempt to change the nature of the game which
worked out.} ({Something like} 13. Bh6 Re8 14. O-O {would be safer, but in
this case, Black continues bringing his pieces into play with a good position.
For example:} Be6 15. Rad1 Qc7 16. f4 f5 17. Bc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4+ Kh8 19. Kh1 Bf6
$15 {and Black has a comfortable game.}) {Despite the result, White's idea
doesn't look objectively good. After the solid} 13... h5 $1 {Jobava would face
serious difficulties continuing his attack, as seen in the following
variations:} 14. O-O-O Ba3+ 15. Kb1 a5 $1 16. Bh6 Re8 17. Qe4 (17. Bxg6 $2 {
is refuted by} Qf6 $1 $19 {[%csl Rg6,Rh6] and White loses a pieces}) 17... Qc7
18. Qa4 (18. Bc4 $2 Bf5 19. Qe3 Nb4 $1 $19) 18... Be7 19. f3 Bd7 20. Bb5 Be6 $1
21. g4 {White's attack might look scary at first sight, but in fact it is
quite the opposite. After} hxg4 22. fxg4 Rec8 23. h5 {Black has the strong
reply} Nb4 $3 {when White is the side facing a devastating attack.} 24. hxg6
Qxc3 25. Rh2 e4 $1 $19 {[%cal Ge7f6] and Black wins.}) (7. Bc4 {was tried by
Gelfand and Ivanchuk. White's idea is to met} Nxe4 {with} ({The most played is
} 7... O-O 8. Qd3 d5 $1 9. exd5 e4 $1 $36 {which seems also promising for
Black.}) 8. Bxf7+ (8. Qd5 $2 Nd6 $19) ({and} 8. O-O Nxc3 9. bxc3 Be7 $17 {
are obviously bad for White.}) 8... Kxf7 9. Qd5+ {However, I still like
Black's position after} Ke8 10. Qxe4 d5 11. Qe2 d4 12. a3 Be7 13. Ne4 Qd5 {
since Black's next moves are simple and good, completing the development and
solving the king's issue. For example:} 14. O-O Bf5 15. f3 Rf8 16. Bd2 Kf7 $15
{[%cal Gf7g8] and Black has a good game.}) (7. Bg5 h6 8. Bxf6 Bxc3+ $1 9. bxc3
Qxf6 $15 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3] is similar to some positions seen after 6.Nf3.}) 7...
Bxc3 {Direct play by Black.} ({Black also has a playable position in case of
both} 7... d6 8. Bd3 {and}) (7... O-O 8. Nd5 $5 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 d6 $11 {but the
text seems a good way of disturbing White's development a bit.}) 8. Bxc3 O-O (
8... Nxe4 {is the most played, but White has the nice resource} 9. Qg4 $1 Nf6 (
9... Ng5 $2 {is bad due to} 10. f4 $1 $16) 10. Qxg7 Rg8 11. Qh6 d5 12. O-O-O
$13 {with a double-edged game, but probably riskier for Black in practice.}) 9.
Qf3 (9. Bd3 {is more natural, but after} d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 {the initiative is
with Black, since} 11. Bd2 $2 {is strongly by} e4 $1 12. Be2 Qf6 $17 {[%csl
Rb2][%cal Gf6g6] and White is suddenly under strong pressure.}) 9... d6 {
Black doesn't need to hurry here. White is not able to control the d5-square
anyway, so we can develop the bishop before pushing the d-pawn.} ({But} 9... d5
{can be played directly as well. The difference is that after} 10. exd5 Qxd5
11. Be2 {[%cal Ga1d1] White has an easy development, though the position is
still balanced.}) 10. h3 ({In case of} 10. Bd3 Bg4 $1 11. Qg3 Be6 {the little
disturbing of the queen might be exploited in Black's favour, for instance:}
12. O-O Nh5 13. Qf3 Nf4 14. Rad1 {and now Black has the strong idea} h5 $1 15.
h3 f5 $1 16. exf5 Bd5 17. Be4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 d5 19. Qf3 Rxf5 $36 {with strong
initiative.}) 10... Be6 11. Bd3 d5 12. O-O ({After} 12. exd5 Nxd5 $15 {[%cal
Yf7f5,Gd5c3] White's position is already a little unpleasant.}) 12... dxe4 13.
Bxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 f6 $11 {The position is objectively balanced, but I even
prefer Black's chances as White's bishop is more passive in this structure.} *

