1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Nf5 {This active jump
is more or less refuted by} d5 $1 ({Of course,} 6... d6 $2 7. Bg5 $16 {is
simply bad for Black.}) 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 $1 ({More precise than} 8...
Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {as now White has} 10. Ne3 Be6 11. Nc4 {[%cal Gc1e3,Yc2c3]
with a harmonious development.}) 9. Qf3 (9. Bd3 {was tried in a few games, but
after} e4 $5 {Black can even play for some advantage.} ({The endgame after} 
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. cxd3 Rb8 $11 {[%cal Gf6d5] is also harmless for
Black.}) 10. Bc4 ({In case of} 10. Qe2 Bb4 11. O-O Qe7 12. Bc4 O-O 13. Bf4 Rad8
{I like Black's position. A nice point is that} 14. Rad1 $2 {is bad in view of}
Bg4 $1 15. f3 Bh5 {when White is already in trouble, for instance:} 16. Rxd8
Rxd8 17. Nxe4 $2 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Bc5+ $1 19. Kh1 Rd4 $19 {and Black wins a piece.
}) 10... Bd6 {The e4-pawn takes space in the centre and allows Black to
develop a strong initiative on the kingside. The following game is a nice
example of how to develop this plan:} 11. h3 O-O 12. Be3 Qe7 13. Qe2 Be5 $1 (
13... Rad8 $2 14. O-O-O $1 {was White's idea.}) 14. O-O Rfe8 15. Rfd1 h6 16.
Bb3 Rac8 17. Na4 Bb8 $1 $19 {[%cal Ge7e5,Ge7c7] and White's position is
already hopeless.}) ({In case of} 9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 {[%csl Gc2] White has problems
with the c2-pawn.} 10. Be3 {is more or less forced, but after} Bxc2 11. Bxa7
Ra8 12. Be3 Rb8 13. b3 Nd5 $36 {the initiative is with Black.}) (9. Ba6 $5 {
is also comfortable for Black after} Bb4 (9... Qb6 10. Qe2 {is White's idea,
with a normal development.}) 10. O-O (10. Bb7 $2 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Rd8+ 12. Bd2
Bxc3 13. bxc3 Ke7 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 14. Bxc6 $2 Rd6 $19 {[%cal Gh8d8]}) 10... O-O
11. Qf3 Bxc2 12. Qxc6 Qb6 {Black is completely fine here.}) 9... Qd7 {This
position was seen in a few recent games, but practice has shown that Black is
ok with correct play.} 10. Bg5 (10. Bc4 {is another logical option.} Be7 (10...
Bxc2 11. Qe2 {[%csl Gc2,Ye5] is the point.}) 11. O-O O-O 12. Rd1 ({Another
game went} 12. Bg5 Bxc2 13. Rac1 $6 (13. Qe2 {was perhaps better, though after}
Bg6 14. Qxe5 Bd6 15. Qe2 Rfe8 $36 {Black has an easier game.}) 13... Bg6 14.
Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Rfd1 Qb7 $17 {and White hadn't enough compensation for the pawn.}
) 12... Qc8 13. Qe2 {Defending against both Bxc2 and Bg4.} (13. Ba6 Qe6 {
should lead to a repetition, since} 14. Bb7 $2 e4 $1 $17 {leaves White in
trouble.}) 13... Qc7 {Black has no problems completing the development here.}
14. h3 Bb4 15. Na4 Rfe8 16. a3 Bf8 17. Nc3 {Fernandez,D (2500)-Jackson,J (2314)
London Classic op 2017 (4) ½-½ Black has a good position and can continue in
many ways here. I like} e4 18. Be3 (18. Bg5 Bd6 $5 19. Bxf6 $6 gxf6 $15 {
is good only for Black, as ideas like Bg6-f5-f4 look very promising.}) 18...
Bd6 19. Rd2 Bh2+ 20. Kh1 Be5 $11 {with a balanced game.}) 10... e4 $1 {This
advance is a nice attempt to disturb White's coordination.} 11. Qd1 (11. Qe2 {
is the most played, but after} Be7 {White needs to solve the development of
the light-squared bishop.} 12. Rd1 (12. Bxf6 $2 Bxf6 13. Nxe4 O-O $1 $17 {
[%cal Rf8e8] is very bad for White.}) 12... Qe6 13. Qc4 Rb8 14. Qxe6 fxe6 $1 {
Now Black can take the initiative.} 15. b3 Nd5 16. Bxe7 Kxe7 17. Na4 {Akopian,
V (2615)-Yakovich,Y (2510) Rostov on Don op 1993 ½-½ Black would have kept
better chances here with} Rhd8 {for example:} 18. Be2 Nb4 $1 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20.
Bd1 Nxa2 $15) 11... Bd6 $1 {A less exploited but very strong idea. Instead of
being worried about doubled pawns on the f-file, Black looks for active
development.} (11... Qe6 {was played by Carlsen and is also enough to get a
good game.} 12. Qd4 Rd8 13. Qa4 Bc5 14. Bc4 Qe5 15. Qxc6+ Bd7 {[%csl Rc6,Rg5]}
16. Bxf6 Bxf2+ $1 17. Kf1 $1 ({But not} 17. Kxf2 $4 Qf4+ $19 {[%cal Rd7c6]})
17... gxf6 18. Qxe4 Bd4 19. Re1 Kf8 $1 $15 {Vachier Lagrave,M (2784) -Carlsen,
M (2862) Chess.com Speed blitz 2020 (3.22) 1-0 Black has more than enough
