1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Nde2 $5 {This looks
like the only viable alternative to 6.Ndb5 can pose practical problems for
Black. It can be found in games of strong players like GM's Ponkratov and
Andreikin and was played by Topalov recently in Norway Chess.} Bc5 $1 {There
is no threat of a check on d6, so Black has time to develop the bishop on an
active diagonal first.} (6... d6 7. g3 $1 {transposes to the Classic Sicilian.}
) (6... Bb4 {is not so unpleasant for White now as after either 6.Nf3 or 6.Nb3.
White has an interesting way to deal with the pin:} 7. a3 Ba5 8. Bg5 $5 (8. b4
Bb6 9. Qd6 $5 {is also possible.}) 8... h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nxe4 11. b4 Nxc3
12. Nxc3 Bb6 13. Nd5 $44 {[%cal Gh2h4] ;Andreikin,D (2726)-Zhigalko,S (2572)
Clash of the Titans blitz 2020 (2) 1-0 and White has nice compensation.}) 7.
Ng3 (7. Be3 $6 {is the second option of the engine and was played in some
games. However, it seems hard to believe that such a move can bring any
advantage for White.} Bxe3 8. fxe3 d6 9. Ng3 (9. Qd2 Be6 10. O-O-O Qa5 $15 {
[%cal Ge8c8] also looks good for Black.}) 9... Be6 10. Bb5 (10. Qd2 {can be
met by} h5 $1 11. O-O-O g6 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4] when Black already has the
initiative. For instance:} 12. Bb5 Rc8 13. Qxd6 Qxd6 14. Rxd6 Ke7 15. Rd2 h4
16. Nge2 Na5 $17 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ya7a6,Yb7b5,Ga5c4] despite the pawn
advantage, White is clearly under pressure here.}) 10... Qb6 11. Qd3 O-O-O 12.
O-O {Cubas,J (2455)-Supi,L (2424) Sao Paulo Hebraica 18th 2015 (7) 0-1} d5 {
was already possible here. After} 13. Bxc6 (13. Rxf6 $2 dxe4 $19) 13... Qxc6
14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nf5 Rhe8 {Black has a better game.} 16. Nxg7 $2 {is
obviously bad in view of} Rg8 $19 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Rg8g1,Rc6h1]}) 7... O-O ({
After} 7... Qb6 8. Qd2 {White has no problems continuing developing with Bc4
and 0-0, and Black has to count with Na4 sometimes.}) (7... d6 {was played in
Topalov's game. Now he went for the interesting idea} 8. Na4 $5 Bb4+ 9. c3 Ba5
10. b4 Bc7 {with a very original position. After the natural moves} 11. Be2 O-O
12. O-O a6 {Topalov,V (2730)-Wang,H (2744) Norway Chess 10th 2022 (7) ½-½
the position is balanced. In the game Topalov even managed to get a small
advantage at some point, but Black was able to neutralize it with correct
defensive play.}) 8. Be2 {The most played, but White has two other natural
ways of developing this bishop.} (8. Bc4 {seems more active, on the other hand
White can face some issues with the exposed g4-square.} d6 9. O-O a6 {I like
this move, avoiding the Na4-idea seen in Topalov-Wag Hao.} (9... Ng4 {looks
aggressive but only leads to a forced draw after} 10. h3 Qh4 11. Qf3 Nd4 12.
Qd3 Be6 $1 13. hxg4 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Nf3+ 15. gxf3 Qxg3+ 16. Kh1 Qh3+ $11) 10. Bg5
(10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 Ne7 12. Bb3 Be6 $11 {is fine for Black.}) 10... h6 11.
Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nd5 Qd8 13. c3 {Ponkratov,P (2641)-Obolenskikh,D (2547)
Cheliabinsk Variation Blitz 2022 (4) 1-0} ({Another game went} 13. Qh5 {
Ivanov,O (2458)-Studer,N (2580) EU-ch Online 2300+ Final 2020 (5) 0-1 A nice
improvement for Black now would be} b5 14. Bb3 a5 15. a3 {and only now} Qg5 $1
{as after} 16. Qxg5 hxg5 17. Nf5 {Black has the option of} Ra7 $5 18. Rfd1 Rd8
{with a nice position.}) {Here I suggest} 13... g6 $5 {keeping the Ng3 away of
f5. Sometimes, Black can also consider developing his play on the kingside by
either h6-h5 or f7-f5. A possible variation could be} 14. b4 Ba7 15. a4 Kg7 16.
Kh1 Be6 17. Qd3 Rc8 18. Rad1 Ne7 {with a similar position as in the game, but
now it's harder to suggest a constructive plan for White. For example:} 19. a5
Qd7 20. Ne3 Bxc4 21. Nxc4 Qe6 $1 22. Ne3 (22. Nxd6 $2 Rcd8 23. c4 Bb8 $1 24. c5
Nc8 $1 $15 {is better for Black.}) 22... Bxe3 23. Qxe3 d5 $11 {and Black is ok.
}) (8. Bd3 {is more solid. Now Black can choose between the solid continuation}
h6 ({Or} 8... Bb4 $5 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 d6 $11 {[%csl Gc2,Gc3] with an
unbalanced game and chances for both sides.}) 9. O-O a6 {After preventing Bg5
and vacating a7 for the bishop, we can play d6 and continue developing our
pieces. Black's position is solid, and White is lacking active ideas. For
example:} 10. Nd5 ({The attacking plan} 10. Nh5 Nxh5 11. Qxh5 d6 12. Kh1 {
[%cal Yf2f4] is not dangerous for Black, as after} Be6 13. f4 exf4 14. Bxf4 {
Black has the nice maneuver} Bd4 $1 {[%cal Gc6e5] which keeps the kingside
safe. For example:} 15. Rf3 Ne5 16. Rg3 Bf2 $1 $17 {and actually White is the
side in danger here.}) (10. Be3 $5 Bxe3 11. fxe3 d6 12. Nd5 {Otherwise Black
would play prophylactic moves like g6-Be6-Kg7, avoiding any idea on the
kingside. Now we have transposed to 10.Nd5.}) 10... d6 11. Be3 (11. c4 {
[%csl Gd4] reinforces the Nd5, but now Black also has an outpost on d4.}) 11...
Nxd5 12. exd5 (12. Bxc5 {can be met by} Nc3 $5 13. bxc3 dxc5 {with a balanced
game after} 14. Bc4 Qc7 15. Bd5 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gc6e7]}) 12... Bxe3 13. fxe3 ({
But not} 13. dxc6 $2 Ba7 14. cxb7 Bxb7 $17 {[%csl Ga7,Gb7] when Black has two
powerful bishops and a promising majority in the centre.}) 13... Ne7 14. c4 f5
{We have a typical structure where both sides can play for the initiative. A
logical development could be} 15. Rc1 (15. Qh5 $2 {is bad due to} Qb6 $1 $17)
15... b6 16. b4 a5 17. a3 g6 18. c5 axb4 19. axb4 bxc5 20. bxc5 Kg7 $11 {
with an equal game.}) 8... Bb4 $5 {Black has many ways to get a playable
position, but I like this principled idea, creating the threats of d5 and Bxc3.
} (8... h6 9. O-O a6 {[%cal Yd7d6] followed by d7-d6 is also possible, with
the same approach as after 8.Bd3.}) 9. Bc4 {Besides wasting one more tempo,
this doesn't prevents the freeing advance.} ({After} 9. O-O $5 Bxc3 10. bxc3 d5
{Black has a nice development and has avoided any problem in the opening.
White's bishops are not particularly dangerous, and the doubled pawns on the
c-file make it very difficult to play for any advantage. For example:} 11. Bf3
({In case of} 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Bc4 Be6 $1 (12... Nxc3 13. Qe1 $44 {gives some
compensation for White.}) 13. Qf3 Ne3 $1 14. Bxe3 Bxc4 15. Rfd1 Qc7 $15 {
I think Black has better practical chances.}) 11... Be6 12. Bg5 (12. Rb1 dxe4
13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Qc7 $15 {also seems easier for Black.}) 12... dxe4 13.
Nxe4 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Rac8 $15 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3][%cal Yb7b6,Gc6a5]
and Black keep some practical chances in the endgame.}) ({In case of} 9. Bd2
Bxc3 10. Bxc3 d5 {I also like Black's position. After something like} 11. Bd3 (
11. exd5 $6 Nxd5 12. Bd2 Be6 13. O-O Qc7 $15 {[%cal Ga8d8,Yf7f5] is more
pleasant for Black.}) 11... Bg4 12. f3 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Bf5 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15.
Bxf5 Qxf5 $11 {Black is completely fine.}) 9... d5 $1 10. exd5 (10. Bxd5 $2 {
is worse in view of} Nxd5 11. exd5 Ne7 $15 {and Black regains the pawn with a
nice position.}) 10... Na5 11. Bd3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxd5 {and Black has a good
game.} 13. O-O Bg4 14. Qe1 Rfe8 15. f3 Be6 16. Bg5 Nd7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga5c4]
Black has a solid position and simple ideas like Rac8-Nc4 to put pressure on
the enemy camp, forcing White to look for active play to avoid being worse.
Still, after something like} 17. Rd1 Qc5+ 18. Be3 Qc7 19. f4 {Black can avoid
any problem. There are many moves here, but I like the simplifying path} Bg4
20. Rb1 exf4 21. Rxf4 Qxf4 $1 22. Bxf4 Rxe1+ 23. Rxe1 Be6 $11 *

