{Due to the fixed pawn structure, in Sveshnikov Variation we can see many
typical endgames. In my opinion, you should start your Sveshnikov journey by
examining the arising endgame positions. In this way, when playing a
middlegame position, you will know exactly what type of endgame you are
looking for. The main focus of this lecture is the endgames arising in the line
} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 ({
I also examine some endgames arising from the line with} 7. Nd5) 7... a6 8. Na3
b5 9. Nd5 {This positional variation is rich in thematic endgames. This could
be explained by the fixed pawn structure. The PGN version of the lecture is
divided into the following topics: 1) Nightmare and Dream Scenarios 2)
Positions with Opposite-Coloured Bishops when Black is Dominating 3) White
Dominates on the Light Squares 4) Endgames with Heavy Pieces 5) Fighting
against White's Queenside Majority in the Endgame} ({In the variation with} 9.
Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 {The play is often very sharp and dynamic. Therefore, it's
very difficult to define typical endgame patterns.}) *

