{[%csl Bd5,Bd1,Bb8,Bf7,Be7][%cal Bd1d3,Be2g4,Bg2g3,Bd3f3,Bg7g6,Bh2h4,Bh4h5,
Bb5b4,Bc3c4,Ba7g1] In my opinion, it makes sense to start by pointing out some
typical endgames that Black should definitely avoid. On the diagram, you can
see such an unfavourable scenario. White enjoys typical domination in a
position with opposite-coloured bishops. In the long run, it will be very
difficult for Black to deal with the pressure along the diagonal a2-g8. While
Black does not have any real counterplay, White can gradually build his
kingside attack by means of simple moves such as Qg4, Rd3-f3, and h2-h4-h5-h6.
The break ...b5-b4 will be always met by c3-c4. Strategically speaking, Black
is almost lost.}  *

