{This is another typical case of domination on the light squares. Since White
has full control in the centre, his long-term plan is based on a kingside
attack. Black's only hope to defend such a position is to exchange the queens.
Let's suppose that White allows this by going for the following cooperative
line - [#]} 1. Qf3 {[%cal Bd1a1,Ba2a4,Ba4b5]} f6 2. Qg3 Kf7 3. Qh3 Ke8 4. Qxd7+
Kxd7 {[%csl Be4,Bd5][%cal Bd7e6,Bg7g6,Bf6f5,Bb8c8,Bc8c5] All of a sudden, we
see that White's advantage has almost evaporated. After putting the king on e6
and the rook on c5, Black will prepare the advance ...f6-f5.} *

