{This typical position with a pawn on d5, represents the perfect scenario for
Black. This type of position with opposite-coloured bishops is clearly
favourable for Black. Whereas there is no active spot for the white bishop,
the black bishop has a lot of potential on the diagonal a7-g1. Combined with
the kingside majority, the strong black bishop can support a devastating
kingside attack. A sample line would be [#]} 1. a4 {[%csl Be2][%cal Ba7g1,
Be7d8,Bd8b6,Bf7f5,Bc7e7,Be5e4,Be7e5,Bf5f4,Ba2a4]} Bd8 $1 {Transferring the
bishop to b6 is our first priority.} 2. axb5 axb5 3. Qb3 Qe7 4. Bxb5 Bb6 {
[%csl Bb6][%cal Bf7f5,Be5e4,Bf5f4,Be4e3,Be7h4,Ba7g1] Black is strategically
winning. White's extra pawn is not important at all. At the same time, Black's
central pawns will start rolling. Also, the black queen as well as the f8-rook
can easily join the attack.} *

