{[%evp 0,60,32,6,48,48,95,72,62,31,37,42,68,38,38,29,34,34,21,23,41,26,22,7,11,
23,14,1,-4,-2,-17,-17,-17,-17,-17,-33,-26,-39,-20,-21,-21,-32,-20,-48,-24,-24,
-25,-85,-31,-80,-47,-169,-141,-175,-135,-204,-145,-143,-143,-153,-120,-125,
-118] Now, we shall see a few examples illustrating the domination of Black's
dark-squared bishop in Sveshnikov endgames. The first game that I would like
to analyze is Polgar, J - Domingues Perez, Lenier. Eve though Black played the
Sicilian Najdorf, the arising structure was quite typical for Sveshnikov as
well. The critical position arises after move 17.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4
cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bc4 O-O 9. O-O Qc7 10. Bb3
Be6 11. Qe2 Rc8 12. Rfd1 b5 13. Bg5 Nbd7 14. Rac1 b4 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. Bxf6 Nxf6
17. exd5 {[%csl Be7,Bb3,Bf7,Be5][%cal Ba7g1] In my opinion, this decision is
positionally wrong. We already know that in this structure, Black has an
advantage in view of the better potential of his bishop. Additionally, he can
always rely on his mobile central majority.} ({In my opinion, better would
have been} 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 {[%csl Bb4,Bb5,Bc3,Be4,Bc2][%cal Bc2c3,Bc1d1,
Bc7c4] Even in this case, however, Black is doing fine because of the pressure
along the c-file. The c2-pawn is an important target. At the same time, White
can never transfer his knight to d5, thus achieving one of his favourable
scenarios.}) 17... Qd7 {[%cal Bb3a4,Ba4c6,Ge7d8,Gd8b6] This is a prophylactic
move against the maneuver Ba4-c6. Simultaneously, Black is preparing to
transfer his own bishop to b6.} 18. Bc4 Qa7 19. c3 bxc3 20. Rxc3 Bd8 {[%cal
Bd8b6]} 21. Ng5 {[%csl Bf6,Bh7,Bg7,Bf7][%cal Bc3f3] Planning Rf3. As a matter
of fact, White does not have any potential to organize a kingside attack.} a5
22. Rf3 Qe7 {[%cal Bd8b6,Bf3f6] Safeguarding the knight and preparing ...Bb6.}
23. b3 a4 {With this move, Black makes sure that his a8-rook can operate via
the a-file.} 24. Rh3 {[%cal Gg5h7,Ge2h5]} g6 {Black needs to prevent the
simple trick Nxh7 followed by Qh5.} 25. Qc2 axb3 26. axb3 Bb6 {[%csl Bb6,Bc4,
Bf7][%cal Bf6g4,Bg5e4,Bf7f5] Once the bishop occupies the diagonal a7-g1,
Black has tremendous attacking potential. White should already reckon with the
threat of ...Ng4.} 27. Rf1 Ng4 28. Ne4 {The most natural continuation.} ({
The move} 28. Nxh7 $2 {loses to} Nxf2 29. Rxf2 Ra1+ $19 {[%cal Bc4f1,Bc8c2]})
28... f5 29. Rg3 Nf6 30. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {[%csl Bg1] We have reached an important
moment. Note that the exchange of the knight does not take the steam out of
Black's attack. As usual, the strong bishop combined with a mobile central
majority would give Black a decisive advantage.} 31. Rd3 Rc7 $1 {[%cal Gc7a7]
Another precise move. Black is planning to penetrate via the a-file.} 32. Qc3
Rca7 33. Rd2 Bd4 34. Qd3 Ra1 {Exchanging the most important defender of the
white king.} 35. g3 Rxf1+ 36. Kxf1 Bc5 {[%csl Bb3][%cal Be5e4] Black is ready
to put his central pawns into motion. The advance ...e5-e4 is coming.} 37. Kg2
e4 38. Qe2 Re8 {[%csl Bg8][%cal Be4e3,Bf5f4,Be8e5] Black's attack is
devastating. The breaks ...e4-e3 and ...f5-f4 are always in the air. White
resigned in just a few moves.} 39. f3 exf3+ 40. Qxf3 Re3 41. Qf1 Qe5 42. Qf4
Qe7 43. Ra2 Re1 44. b4 Be3 45. Qf3 Rg1+ 46. Kh3 Qg5 {[%cal Bg5h6] 0-1 Black
wins.} 47. Ra8+ Kg7 {[%csl Ba7][%cal Be3a7]} 0-1

