{To the untrained eye, the position might appear to be equal. We already know,
however, that Black enjoys a huge advantage. He just needs to transfer his
bishop to the diagonal a7-g1. Therefore, the Chinese GM starts with the move} 
28... Bg5 $1 {[%csl Ba5][%cal Bc7c5,Bg5d8,Bd8b6,Ba7g1] planning ...Qc5
followed by ...Bd8-b6. In this case, Black will enjoy tremendous pressure
against the f2-pawn.} 29. g3 Qc5 {[%csl Bb5]} 30. Kg2 $2 {This passive move
allows Black to achieve his desired setup.} ({More tenacious would have been} 
30. Qxa5 {Nevertheless, after} Qc2 31. Qe1 Bd2 32. Qd1 Qxe4 {Black is the one
who is calling the shots.}) 30... Bd8 31. Qd2 Bb6 {Mission completed! Now,
White should not only reckon with Black's kingside attack but also he should
deal with the potentially dangerous a5-pawn.} 32. Bg4 Qc4 33. h6+ Kf8 34. Qe1
f5 ({Even more precise would have been} 34... a4 $19 {[%csl Ba4,Bg2][%cal
Ba4a3,Ba3a2]} 35. Rb4 Qa2 {[%csl Bf2,Bb5][%cal Ba4a3,Bb6c5] with ...Bc5 and ...
a4-a3 to follow. Also, White should always keep an eye on the f2-pawn. Black
is winning.}) 35. Rc1 Qxe4+ 36. Qxe4 fxe4 37. Rc4 $2 (37. Rc6 Ke7 38. Bd1 $17)
37... Bc5 38. Rxe4 Rxb5 $19 {Later on, Black managed to easily convert his
advantage.} 39. f4 Rb2+ 40. Kh3 Rb4 41. Rxb4 axb4 42. Bd1 exf4 43. gxf4 Kf7 44.
Kg4 Kf6 45. Bc2 Bb6 46. f5 g5 47. Ba4 Bd8 48. Bb3 Be7 49. Bc2 Ke5 50. f6 Kxf6
51. Bxh7 Bf8 52. Kf3 Ke5 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

