{In the next example, we will see that our dark-squared bishop can dominate
even in the endgame. In this position, Black should decide how to deal with
the d5-knight. At this point, GM Eljanov took a subtle positional decision -} 
21... Bxd5 $1 {When White has a pawn on c4, we can even allow our opponent to
recapture on d5 with a piece. The thing is that with a pawn on c4, White can
never activate his bishop along the a2-g8 diagonal.} 22. Qxd5 ({Even worse
would be} 22. cxd5 {since after} Bd8 {[%cal Bd8b6,Bf7f5,Ba7f7,Bb8d8,Bd8h4]
followed by ...Bb6, ...f7-f5, and ...Raf7 Black has tremendous attacking
potential.}) 22... Rc8 {[%csl Bc4,Be2] Black is planning to follow with ...Rc5.
At the same time, the move ...Rc8 rules out any c4-c5 ideas.} 23. f4 Rc5 24.
Qd2 exf4 {[%csl Be7] After this move, the black bishop is getting even more
powerful. Eljanov's next step will be to redirect the bishop to the diagonal
a1-h8.} 25. Qxf4 Bf8 {[%csl Bc5,Bf8,Be5] The bishop is heading to the
important e5-square. White has nothing to oppose Black's dark-square strategy.}
26. Rd5 Rxd5 27. exd5 {[%csl Be2,Bf7,Bf8,Be5,Bh1][%cal Ba2g8,Bb8f8,Bf8h6] Once
again, the pawn structure has been transformed. White's bishop is still
completely useless. Black is ready to transfer the bishop to e5. Afterwards,
he will consider bringing the queen to the kingside. In some cases, the
manoeuvre...Qf8-h6 might become possible.} Qb6 28. Bg4 Bg7 29. Re1 Be5 30. Qe3
Qxe3 31. Rxe3 {Even in the endgame, Black has a huge advantage in view of his
superior bishop.} Kg7 {[%csl Be5][%cal Bf7f5,Bg7f6,Bh7h5,Bh5h4,Bg6g5,Bg5g4,
Bf6g5,Ba5a4] Eljanov is ready to start gaining space on the kingside. At the
same time, he can always create a second weakness by means of the break ...
a5-a4.} 32. Bd1 h5 33. g3 f5 34. Kg2 ({The exchange sacrifice does not work in
view of} 34. Rxe5 dxe5 {[%cal Bg7f6,Be5e4,Bf6e5]} 35. c5 Kf6 36. d6 Ke6 $19 {
when Black manages to easily stop the pawns.}) 34... Kf6 35. Re1 Rc7 36. Re2
Kg5 37. Bc2 h4 38. Bd3 Kf6 39. Rc2 Rc8 40. Re2 Rh8 {[%csl Bh3,Bh2,Bg3][%cal
Bh4h3,Be5g3] This is an important moment. Under favourable circumstances,
Black will play ...h4-h3, fixing the h2-pawn. In this case, White will always
need to reckon with possible ...Bxg3 ideas. Afterwards, Black will need to
create a second weakness and win the game.} 41. Re3 Rh7 42. Bc2 Rh6 43. Bd3 Rh8
44. Bc2 h3+ {Finally, Eljanov goes for this important move.} 45. Kf1 g5 46. Rf3
f4 47. g4 Bd4 $19 {[%cal Gf6e5,Gd4e3,Ge5d4] Black has a decisive advantage.
After putting the bishop on e3, he can easily penetrate with the king via the
dark squares. As you can see, the white bishop is completely useless in this
position. Eljanov managed to convert his advantage without too much of an
effort.} 48. Bd3 Ke5 49. Bg6 Be3 50. Ke2 Kd4 51. Bh5 Kc3 52. c5 dxc5 53. Rxh3
Rh7 54. Rf3 Rd7 55. h4 gxh4 56. Rh3 Rxd5 57. Kf3 Kb2 58. Bf7 Rd2 59. g5 Rf2+
60. Ke4 Rg2 61. g6 Kxa2 62. Rxh4 Ka3 63. Rh8 c4 64. Bxc4 Rxg6 65. Rh5 Bb6 66.
Kxf4 Rc6 67. Rb5 a4 68. Bd5 Rh6 69. Kg5 Be3+ 70. Kf5 axb3 71. Ra5+ Kb2 72. Ke4
Bb6 73. Ra8 Rh4+ 74. Kf3 Bd4 75. Rb8 Bc3 76. Rg8 Rd4 77. Rg2+ Rd2 78. Rxd2+
Bxd2 79. Ke2 Kc2 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

