[EventDate "2022.??.??"]
[SourceVersionDate "2022.07.25"]

{This is another example of an endgame where the dark-squared bishop dominates
his light-squared counterpart.} 20... Bxd5 {As we know, Black is usually more
than happy to force his opponent to recapture on d5 with a pawn.} 21. cxd5 {
[%csl Bg5,Bb6][%cal Bc1c8]} g6 22. Rfd1 Rxa1 $1 {An important move. Before
going for the manoeuvre...Bd8-b6, Black needs to make sure that White does not
have Rac1. In this structure, establishing firm control of the c-file is
White's main strategy.} 23. Rxa1 Bd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6] Finally, Black goes for
this thematic manoeuvre.} 24. Qe3 {Seeing Black's huge attacking potential,
Chigaev is trying to bail out in an inferior endgame.} Qxe3 25. fxe3 Bb6 26.
Kf2 Rc8 {Black's play is natural and easy.} 27. Re1 Kf8 28. Bh3 Rc2+ 29. Re2
Rc7 30. Ke1 b3 {[%csl Rb2,Bh3] As we have seen from the previous example,
fixing the opponent's pawns is an important endgame strategy.} 31. Kd2 Ke7 32.
Kd3 h5 {[%csl Bb2][%cal Bg3g4] Shirov immediately starts creating another
weakness. This time on the kingside. This move allows Black to shut the
g2-bishop down.} 33. Bg2 $2 ({A bit more tenacious would have been} 33. g4 {
Nevertheless, after} h4 34. g5 Rc1 35. Kd2 Rg1 {White will hardly manage to
survive.}) 33... g5 $1 34. h3 g4 $19 {[%csl Bg3] White is already playing
without a bishop. Additionally, the g3-pawn is an important weakness. Shirov
managed to easily convert his decisive advantage.} 35. hxg4 hxg4 36. Rf2 Rc1
37. Bf1 Ba5 38. Bg2 Rg1 39. Kc4 Be1 40. Re2 Bxg3 41. Kxb3 Kf6 42. Kc4 Kg5 43.
b4 Rb1 44. b5 Be1 45. b6 Ba5 46. Rf2 Bxb6 47. Rxf7 Bxe3 48. Bf1 Rxf1 49. Rxf1
g3 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

[Event "FIDE World Cup"]
