[Black "Gelfand, Boris"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "B33"]
[WhiteElo "2511"]
[BlackElo "2741"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/5ppp/2npb3/p2Np1b1/1pP1P3/3Q2P1/PPN2PBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 16"]
[PlyCount "53"]
[EventDate "2022.??.??"]
[SourceVersionDate "2022.07.25"]

{In this example, we will see that even in the endgame with a pawn down the
dark-squared bishop usually holds the position quite easily. In this position,
the big Sveshnikov expert Boris Gelfand played} 16... Bxd5 {[%csl Bc4,Bg2]
[%cal Ba2g8] We know that this exchange is always justified when White's pawn
is on c4.} 17. cxd5 {[%cal Bc6b8,Bc6e7]} Nb8 {[%cal Bb8a6,Ba6c5] The knight is
heading for the c5-square.} 18. h4 {[%csl Bc1][%cal Bg5h6,Bg5d8,Bd8b6]} Bh6 {
[%csl Bh6][%cal Bb8a6,Ba6c5,Bd8b6,Ba8a7,Bf7f5,Ba7f7,Bf8f1] The bishop should
control the c1-square. Otherwise, White will occupy the important c-file. If
allowed, Black will build an attack by making simple moves such as ...Na6-c5, .
..Qb6, ...Ra7 followed by ...f7-f5 and ... Raf7.} ({After} 18... Be7 19. Bh3 {
[%csl Bc8][%cal Bc2e3,Ba1c1,Bc1c4,Be1c1,Bf1c1] White has a huge positional
advantage since Black cannot fight for the c-file.}) 19. a3 Na6 {This move
marks the beginning of a forced sequence.} 20. axb4 Nxb4 21. Nxb4 axb4 22. Qc4
b3 23. Rxa8 Qxa8 24. Qxb3 Bd2 {The bishop is trying to find a route to the
diagonal a7-g1.} 25. Qb6 Qb8 26. Qxb8 Rxb8 27. Rb1 Bc3 28. b3 Ra8 {Despite
being a pawn down, due to his superior bishop, Black easily holds this endgame.
In a few moves, the opponents agreed to a draw.} 29. b4 Ra1 30. Rxa1 Bxa1 31.
Bh3 Kf8 32. Kg2 Ke7 33. f4 Kf6 34. Kf3 Bc3 35. b5 Bd4 36. Bd7 h6 37. Bg4 Bb6
38. Bh5 g6 39. Bg4 Bd4 40. Bd7 Bb6 41. Bc8 Bd4 42. Bd7 Bb6 {1/2-1/2 The game
is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

