{[#] Now, we shall take a look at several examples where White dominates in
positions with opposite-coloured bishops. This scenario usually happens when
the white bishop manages to occupy the diagonal a2-g8 while his black
counterpart is far away from the diagonal a7-g1. In such cases, White usually
wins by means of a kingside attack. The following example is quite
characteristic.} 21. Rfd1 Be7 {[%csl Bd3,Bf3][%cal Be2g4,Bd5d3,Bb3g8,Bd3f3,
Bf3g3,Bg3h3,Bh2h4,Bh4h5]} 22. Qg4 {White immediately starts transferring his
pieces to the kingside. Black does not have any counterplay in this position.}
a5 23. R5d3 {Freeing the d5-square for the bishop and preparing to bring the
rook towards the kingside.} a4 24. Bd5 Qc7 25. a3 $1 {I like this little pawn
move. Now, Black cannot even dream about queenside counterplay.} Kh8 26. Rh3 g6
27. Ba2 Qc8 28. Qe2 {[%csl Bb5,Ba4][%cal Be2e3,Be3h6,Bd1d5,Ba2b1,Bb1d3] This
move indicates White's intention to combine his kingside attack with pressure
on the queenside weaknesses. Besides the threat of Qe3-h5, White is also
planning to put pressure on b5 by means of Rd5 followed by the manoeuvre
Bb1-d3.} f5 {Black is desperately trying to create at least some counterplay.
In reality, however, this move only makes White's task easier.} 29. exf5 Rxf5
30. Bb1 Rf6 31. Rf3 {Exchanging the most important defender of the king.} Qc5
32. Rxf6 Bxf6 33. Be4 Be7 34. g3 Kg7 35. Kg2 Rf8 36. h4 {The advance h4-h5
will further weaken Black's kingside.} h6 37. Rd5 Qb6 38. Rd2 h5 39. Qd3 {
Black cannot hold the numerous weaknesses in his camp. The game ended in just
a few moves.} Rf6 40. Qd5 Qc5 41. Qb7 {Finally, White penetrates via the light
squares. The game is over.} Rf7 42. Bd5 {1-0 White wins.} 1-0

