[PlyCount "71"]
[EventDate "2022.??.??"]
[SourceVersionDate "2022.07.25"]

{White enjoys typical domination on the light squares, thanks to his powerful
d5-knight. As we have already discussed in the beginning of the lecture, in
such positions Black does not have any counterplay. Vuckovic started with the
logical} 21. Rfd1 {exchanging Black's only active piece.} Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 O-O
23. Qd3 {Since White is dominating in the centre, he can start playing on the
wings. The potential kingside attack can be combined with gaining space on the
queenside. Additionally, Black should reckon with the pressure on the d6-pawn.}
Qa3 24. Qc2 g6 25. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] This move introduces the threat of
h2-h4-h5 under favourable circumstances.} f5 $2 {In an attempt to quickly
organize counterplay, Black creates serious kingside weaknesses.} ({Black
should have adopted a waiting policy. For example, a normal move would be} 
25... Qc5 26. c4 Kg7 27. Qd3 Qc8 28. Kg2 Qc5 29. h4 {[%csl Bh6,Bd5,Bd6][%cal
Bh4h5,Bh5h6] White starts his kingside play. The h-pawn can go all the way to
h6.} h5 {[%csl Bh5,Bd3,Bd1][%cal Bd1d3,Bg3g4,Bh5g4,Bd1g4,Bh4h5]} 30. Rd2 {
[%cal Gd3e2,Ge2d1] White is preparing to transfer his queen to d1. The idea
will be to combine the pressure on d6 with kingside threats. The d1-queen will
be supporting the advance g3-g4.} Qc8 31. Qe2 Qc5 32. Qd1 Ba5 33. Rd3 {[%csl
Bd5][%cal Bg3g4] White is ready to follow with g3-g4. Black is in a
strategically difficult situation.}) 26. exf5 Rxf5 27. b4 {Black should reckon
with Rd3 followed by c3-c4, thus trapping the queen.} b5 28. Ne3 Rf6 29. Ng4
Re6 30. Qd2 $18 {[%cal Gd2d5] The queen is ready to occupy the d5-square.
Black is completely lost. Later on, Vuckovic won without any difficulties.} Kf7
31. f4 Bb6+ 32. Kg2 h5 33. Nh6+ Kg7 34. f5 Rf6 35. g4 Qa4 36. g5 Rxf5 37. Nxf5+
gxf5 38. Qxd6 Qc2+ 39. Kh3 Bd4 40. cxd4 Qxd1 41. Qxe5+ Kg8 42. Qxf5 Qe2 43. d5
Qxa2 44. Qe6+ Kg7 45. Qe5+ Kg6 46. Qf6+ Kh7 47. Qf7+ Kh8 48. Qxh5+ Kg8 49. Qe8+
Kg7 50. Qe5+ Kg6 51. Qf6+ Kh7 52. Qf7+ Kh8 53. g6 Qb3+ 54. Kh4 Qc4+ 55. Kg5
Qc1+ 56. Qf4 {1-0 White wins.} 1-0

[Event "WchT 8th"]
