[WhiteTeam "Hungary"]
[BlackTeam "Ukraine"]
[WhiteTeamCountry "HUN"]
[BlackTeamCountry "UKR"]

{In this example, we will see how easily Black holds endgames with heavy
pieces in Sveshnikov type of structure. In this concrete position, Black's
counterplay provides more than sufficient compensation for the relative
weakness of the d6-pawn.} 30... h5 {It is very important to prevent White from
expanding with h4-h5.} 31. Rd1 Qa7 {[%cal Ba6a2] Moiseenko immediately starts
creating counterplay. Now, the threat is ...Ra2.} 32. Rd2 Kg7 33. Qd1 Ra1 34.
Qf3 Qa6 35. Rd5 Rc1 {[%cal Bc4c5,Bc1c3] Black not only prevents the advance
c4-c5 but also prepares ... Rc3. It turns out that the weakness on b3 is a
significant factor in this position. The following sequence forces an
immediate draw.} 36. Rb5 Rc3 37. Qd1 Qa8 38. Qd5 Qxd5 39. cxd5 Rxb3 40. Rb6 $11
{The draw is obvious.} f5 41. exf5 gxf5 42. Rxd6 Rd3 43. Rb6 b3 44. d6 Kf7 45.
Rb7+ Ke6 46. d7 Ke7 47. Kf1 e4 48. Kg2 Kd8 49. Kf1 Rd1+ 50. Kg2 Rb1 51. Kh2 Rb2
52. Kg1 Ke7 53. Kf1 Rb1+ 54. Kg2 Kd8 55. Kh2 Ke7 56. Kg2 Rb2 57. Kg1 Kd8 58.
Kf1 Rb1+ 59. Kg2 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "Catalunya-ch"]
[Site "Barcelona"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "2.2"]
[White "Asis Gargatagli, Hipolito"]
[Black "Alsina Leal, Daniel"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "B33"]
