[BlackElo "2540"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r5k1/6pp/3pp3/2q1p3/1pP1P2P/1P4P1/r1Q2PK1/3R1R2 w - - 0 28"]
[PlyCount "73"]
[EventDate "2022.??.??"]
[SourceVersionDate "2022.07.25"]

{The same type of endgame with heavy pieces can be practically difficult for
Black when he has doubled pawns on e6 and e5. This pawn formation usually
arises when light-squared bishops have been exchanged on the e6-square.
Black's main problem in this position is the vulnerability of his king. In
addition, he should always take care of the d6-pawn.} 28. Qd3 R8a6 {[%csl Bb3,
Bd6][%cal Bg8f7,Bf7e7]} 29. Rd2 {White is interested in exchanging a pair of
rooks in order to limit Black's counterplay.} h6 {I am not sure whether this
move was called for. In the future, White might use the weak g6-square.} 30.
Rfd1 Kh7 31. Qf3 {[%csl Bd6,Bh7][%cal Bd1d6,Bf3g4,Bh4h5] White is ready to
combine his pressure on d6 with active actions on the kingside. One of the
ideas is to follow with Qg4 and h4-h5.} Rxd2 32. Rxd2 Qc6 33. Qg4 {[%csl Bb3]
[%cal Bc6e8,Ba6a3]} Ra1 $6 {This is already an inaccuracy.} ({The computer
holds the position after} 33... Qe8 {Practically speaking, however, the
position remains unpleasant for Black.}) 34. h5 Kh8 35. Qg6 Ra6 36. c5 $6 {
This is not the most precise continuation.} ({After} 36. Rd3 Qc8 37. g4 $18 {
[%csl Be6,Be5][%cal Gg4g5] White is winning on the spit. Black cannot
simultaneously prevent g4-g5 and take care of the vulnerable central pawns.})
36... Qxc5 37. Qe8+ Kh7 38. Qxe6 {White's position remains significantly
better and he eventually won the game.} Qc3 39. Rd5 Qc2 40. Qg6+ Kh8 41. Qe8+
Kh7 42. Qg6+ Kh8 43. Rb5 Ra8 44. Rb7 Rg8 45. Rd7 Qxb3 46. Qxd6 Qc3 47. Rc7 Qd4
48. Qxd4 exd4 49. Rb7 Rd8 50. Rxb4 Kg8 51. Kf3 Kf7 52. Ke2 Kf6 53. f4 d3+ 54.
Kd2 Ra8 55. Rb3 Ra2+ 56. Kxd3 Rh2 57. g4 Rg2 58. Rb6+ Kf7 59. Rg6 Rg1 60. Kd4
Ra1 61. e5 Ra4+ 62. Ke3 Rb4 63. Rd6 Ra4 64. Rd4 {1-0 White wins.} 1-0

