{[#] This is one more example with doubled e-pawns. This time, with more
pieces on the board.} 24. Ne3 {This position requires a more detailed
examination. The advantages of the black doubled pawns on the e-file are often
overestimated. True, Black controls the d5-square now, but he has a lot of
other weaknesses. Black would certainly prefer to have his pawn on h7, but
alas, now he must deal with the weakness on g6 as well. As long as the queens
are on the board with other pieces, White will always keep pressure in the
centre and on the kingside. It is very important that White hasn't advanced
the pawn from h2 yet, which keeps his pawn structure on the kingside very
flexible. In my opinion, Black should avoid such static positions in the
Sveshnikov Sicilian, although there are strong players who consider them equal
(but I've also seen them losing such "equal" positions when playing passively).
The present game is one more proof that it is highly unpleasant to sit and
wait in a position full of weaknesses, even if the opponent has no direct way
of exploiting them. I believe that Black should try some sort of counterplay
on the queenside instead of waiting passively for White to start the assault
on the kingside.} Qe7 (24... b4 $1 25. cxb4 (25. axb4 axb4 26. c4 {loses the
pawn:} Bxe3 27. Qxe3 Rxc4) 25... axb4 26. a4 b3 $1 $132) 25. Rd3 Rf8 $6 26. f3
Bh4 $2 {Completely losing the thread. Potentially White's knight is much
stronger than the bishop and therefore the bishop had to be exchanged on e3,
even if it didn't mean the end of suffering for Black.} (26... Bxe3+ 27. Rxe3
$14) 27. Qg6 Rf6 28. Qh5 Rf8 29. Rfd1 $16 {Now White has a stable positional
advantage and the next part is very instructive.} Rc6 30. g3 Bg5 31. Nc2 $1 {
Due to Black's strategic mistakes, White has achieved a perfect position: he
has kept the knight and prevented the counterplay with b5-b4. The next stage
is to advance the kingside pawns while keeping up the pressure on d6.} Qd7 32.
h4 Bd8 33. Kg2 Qe7 34. Qg4 Bb6 {In this position the transfer of the bishop to
the queenside only helps White but is difficult to organise a defence anyway.}
(34... Qd7) 35. h5 $1 Kh8 $6 36. Kh3 $1 Rf7 37. Ne1 a4 $2 38. Ng2 Bc7 (38...
Kg8 39. f4 exf4 40. Nxf4 {changes nothing - Black cannot keep material
equality.}) 39. f4 $1 $18 Rc4 40. Nh4 Kh7 41. fxe5 dxe5 42. Rd7 Qe8 (42... Qxd7
43. Rxd7 Rxd7 44. Qg6+ $18) 43. Qg6+ Kg8 44. R1d3 {White wins easily thanks to
his light-square domination.} Rc6 45. Rxf7 Qxf7 46. Qxf7+ Kxf7 47. Rd7+ Kf6 (
47... Kg8 48. Ng6 Bd6 49. Rb7 Rc5 50. Rb6 $18) 48. Ng6 Bd6 49. Kg4 Rb6 50. Nh8
{Besides his miserable structure Black is having problems with the king, which
even in the endgame finds itself in a mating net.} Be7 51. Rd3 Bc5 52. Rf3+ Ke7
53. Rf7+ Ke8 54. Rxg7 Be3 (54... Rd6 55. Rg8+ Kd7 56. Nf7 Rd2 57. Rd8+ $18) 55.
Rg8+ Ke7 56. Ng6+ Kf6 57. Rf8+ Kg7 58. Rf3 Bc1 59. Rf2 Rd6 60. Rc2 Rd1 61. Nxe5
Re1 62. Nc6 Rxe4+ 63. Kf3 Re1 64. Nd4 e5 65. Nxb5 e4+ 66. Kg4 e3 67. c4 Bd2 68.
c5 Rd1 69. Nd4 Ba5 70. Nf5+ {1-0 White wins.} 1-0

