{This example taken from the practice of the great Sveshnikov expert GM Vasil
Spasov shows the power of the kingside majority in Sveshnikov type of
structure. This structure arises from the line with 7.Nd5. As you can see,
Black has already executed the favourable exchange of the dark-squared bishops.
In this position, Black played} 17... a5 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Bd7c5] securing the
c5-square for the knight and immobilizing White's queenside majority.} 18. Nb5
{It's not entirely clear what exactly the knight is doing on b5.} Nc5 19. Rad1
Qe7 20. Rfe1 Bd7 21. Nc3 {Obviously, White cannot allow ...Bxb5. In such a
case the black knight will dominate the light-square bishop.} Rae8 22. Bf1 Qf6
23. f4 {This move only allows Black to put his kingside majority into motion.
On the other hand, it's already difficult to provide White with a good piece
of advice.} exf4 24. Qxf4 g5 25. Qf2 f4 {Black already gained a lot of space
on the kingside. At the same time, White's queenside play hasn't even started.}
26. Rxe8 {White decides to force the transition in a hopeless endgame.} Rxe8
27. Re1 Rxe1 28. Qxe1 Kf7 29. Be2 Qd4+ 30. Qf2 Qxf2+ 31. Kxf2 {[%csl Bd7,Bc5,
Bh7,Bg5,Bf4]} Kf6 {[%cal Gf6e5,Ge5d4] The black king is ready to penetrate
White's position via the d4-square. We can see the tremendous difference in
the activity of the minor pieces.} 32. h3 Ke5 33. Kf3 h5 {[%cal Bg5g4,Be5d4]}
34. g4 fxg3 35. Kxg3 h4+ 36. Kg2 Ne4 37. Nd1 Kd4 $19 {Black is completely
winning and White resigned in a few moves.} 38. b3 b6 39. Bf3 Nc3 40. Nf2 Bf5
41. Ng4 Bxg4 42. Bxg4 Nxa2 43. Kf3 Nc1 44. Be6 Nxb3 45. Kg4 a4 46. Bf5 Nd2 47.
Kxg5 a3 48. Kxh4 a2 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

