{This is another instructive example in which Black demonstrates how to fight
against the opponent's queenside majority.} 21. b4 $2 {[%csl Bb6] This advance
is premature.} (21. Rac1 $14) 21... Bc2 $1 {[%csl Bd1,Bd2][%cal Bd2c2,Bg5e3]
An unpleasant surprise for White.} 22. Rdc1 (22. Rf1 $2 Qxb6 23. f4 Bxf4 24.
Rxf4 Qd8 25. Rg4 Bg6 $17) 22... Qxb6 23. Bxb6 Bxd2 24. Rxc2 Bxb4 25. Rb1 a5 $1
{[%cal Ba2a3,Be8f6,Bf6d7]} (25... Bc5+ 26. Bxc5 dxc5 27. Rb6 {[%csl Bb7,Bd6]
[%cal Bc2b2,Bd5d6]}) 26. Rb3 Nf6 27. a3 Nd7 $1 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Bb6e3,Bb4c5,
Bd7c5,Bf7f5]} 28. axb4 Nxb6 29. bxa5 Na4 30. Ra2 Nc5 31. Rb6 Rfd8 {[%cal Bg8f8,
Bf8e7,Bb8a8,Ba8a7,Bd8a8,Bb6b5,Bb7b6] In result Black has a better knight
versus passive White`s bishop and later Aveskulov won the game.} 32. Bd1 Ra8
33. Bc2 Kf8 34. Kf2 Ke7 {[%csl Bc2]} 35. Ke3 Ra7 36. Kd2 Rda8 37. Rb5 Ra6 38.
Kc3 b6 39. Kb4 Nb7 40. Rb2 bxa5+ 41. Ka3 Nc5 {[%csl Bc2,Bd5][%cal Be4d5]} 42.
Rxc5 dxc5 43. Rb7+ Kd6 44. Rxf7 R6a7 45. Rf5 Rb8 46. Ba4 Rab7 47. g4 Rb1 48.
Ka2 R8b2+ 49. Ka3 Rb4 50. Ka2 R1b2+ 51. Ka3 Rb1 52. Ka2 Rxa4+ 53. Kxb1 Rb4+ 54.
Ka2 Rxc4 55. Rf7 g5 56. Rf6+ Kxd5 57. Rxh6 Rf4 58. Rg6 Rxf3 59. Rxg5 Rh3 60.
Rg8 e4 61. g5 Kd4 62. g6 Rxh2+ 63. Kb1 Rg2 64. g7 Ke3 65. Kc1 a4 66. Kd1 a3 67.
Ra8 Rg1+ 68. Kc2 Rxg7 69. Rxa3+ Ke2 70. Rh3 e3 71. Rh2+ Kf1 72. Kd3 e2 73. Rh1+
Kg2 74. Re1 Kf3 75. Rh1 c4+ 76. Kd2 Rd7+ 77. Kc2 Kg2 78. Re1 Kf2 {0-1 Black
wins.} 0-1

