{[%evp 0,42,28,33,60,51,46,38,38,38,45,38,37,37,44,3,3,3,6,6,6,6,6,-27,0,12,10,
17,17,22,41,34,41,33,33,33,39,42,79,55,52,52,26,-20,-15]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10.
Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 b4 12. Nc2 {A set-up which has lately gained much in
popularity. The position of Nd5 has been reinforced but at the cost of
exposing the d4-square. Black is, therefore often directing the queen to the
c5 and the subtle} O-O {, instead of the most popular 12....a5, makes sense.}
13. g3 (13. Be2 a5 14. O-O (14. Bg4 Be6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Bxe6 Qxe6 ({or} 
16... fxe6 17. O-O Rfd8 $11) 17. Qd3 {White has invested time to exchange a
couple of minor pieces, thus reducing the opponent's active possibilities. Now
he is hoping to exert pressure on the vulnerable d6-pawn and claim a long-term
edge.} Nd8 $5 {[%cal Gd8b7] A relatively new plan to improve the knight. We
will see more of this rerouting to the more active c5-square.} 18. Ne3 Nb7 19.
Rd1 Ra6 $1 {[%cal Gb7c5] An extra and very effective possibility for defending
the only weakness.} 20. O-O Nc5 21. Qc2 Rb8 $11 {[%cal Gb4b3,Ga5a4]}) 14... Bg5
15. Qd3 (15. Bg4 Be6 $11 {[%cal Gg7g6]}) 15... Be6 16. Rad1 (16. a3 bxa3 17.
Nxa3 Nd4 $11 {[%csl Gd4]}) (16. Rfd1 g6 17. a3 bxa3 18. Rxa3 Rb8 19. Qc3 Qc8
$132 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4]}) 16... g6 {[%cal Gg8g7,Gf7f5]} (16... Qb8 $5 {deserves
attention, the queen is supporting the further expansion with a5-a4 and can
reach the nice c5-forepost as well}) 17. a3 $6 {Here, after the queenside rook
has left its initial location, this break lacks impact and the b-file will
serve Black -} bxa3 ({or} 17... Qb8 18. axb4 Bxd5 19. b5 Be6 20. bxc6 Rc8 21.
b3 Rxc6 $15 {Liu - Grischuk, China, 2019}) 18. Qxa3 Qb8 $15) (13. h4 {is
closely connected with the text move, here the ambitious idea to restrict ?f6
and eventually, the hunt for the other bishop from the h3-square will be
examined.} Be6 14. g3 {[%cal Gf1h3]} (14. Qf3 Be7) 14... a5 15. Bh3 a4 {
[%cal Gb4b3]} (15... g6 $5 16. h5 Bg5) 16. Kf1 (16. Nce3 Nd4 {[%csl Gd4]})
16... b3 17. Nce3 Nd4 {[%csl Gd4]} 18. Kg2 Qc8 $5 $146 (18... Rb8) 19. axb3
axb3 20. Rxa8 Qxa8 21. h5 (21. Nxf6+ gxf6) 21... h6 22. Qd3 (22. Nf5 Bxf5 23.
Bxf5 Rb8 $11) (22. Nxf6+ gxf6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ga8a2]}) 22... Bg5 $132 {
[%cal Ga8a2]}) ({Indeed, the activation of ?f6 is a priority task and} 13. Qf3
{is challenging it:} Bh4 $5 {A funny move.} (13... Bg5 14. h4 Bh6 {is the
common continuation -} 15. g4 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gg4g5]} (15. g3 f5 $36) 15... f6
$1 16. Be2 (16. Qg3 Be6 $132) (16. Rg1 Be6 17. Bd3 Ra7 18. Kf1 g6 $132 {
Kantans - Shirov, Jurmala, 2016}) 16... Be6 17. Rd1 a5 18. Qg3 Ra7 19. Rg1 g6
$13) 14. g3 Qa5 $1 {The unexpected point and due exactly to the delayed a6-a5
advance.} 15. b3 (15. gxh4 b3+ 16. Qc3 Qxc3+ 17. bxc3 bxc2 18. Bd3 Rb8 19. Bxc2
Be6 20. O-O-O Rfc8 $11 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4]}) 15... Bd8 {[%cal Gd8b6]} 16. Bg2 (16.
Bd3 Qc5 17. h4 a5 $11 {[%cal Ga5a4] Bellahcene - Salem, Dubai, 2021}) 16... Bb6
{An exquisite cruise of this bishop. White would not definitely like to
surrender the d4-square, so} 17. Nxb6 Qxb6 18. O-O Be6 19. Rfd1 Qc5 20. Rd3 a5
$11 {[%cal Ga5a4]} 21. Rad1 a4 {[%cal Ga8a2] A typical Sveshnikov middlegame
has arisen, in which Black's queenside play is counterbalancing his backward
d-pawn.}) ({Black obtains excellent play after the greedy} 13. Ncxb4 Nxb4 14.
Nxb4 Qb6 {, for example} 15. Nd5 (15. Qd2 $6 Rb8) (15. Nd3 $2 Bb7 16. f3 {
is just asking for trouble after} Bh4+ 17. g3 Bg5 $17 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf7f5]})
15... Qxb2 16. Be2 (16. Bd3 Bd8 17. O-O Qd4 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 16... Bd8 17.
O-O Qa3 $11 {[%cal Ga3c5,Gc8e6]}) 13... Be6 (13... a5 14. Bg2 Bg5 {is still
leading to the main line.}) 14. Bg2 Bxd5 $5 {In combination with the next move
- a direct shot at equality.} ({Indeed,} 14... a5 {is the last chance to
transpose.}) 15. cxd5 (15. Qxd5 {deserves attention, for the jump needs the
preparatory} Qb6 16. O-O {and only now} Nd4 (16... Rfb8 $5) 17. Nxd4 exd4 18.
Qf5 ({White's compensation after} 18. e5 $6 dxe5 19. c5 Qb5 {is doubtful}) ({
also, the location of his centralized ?d5 is very picturesque after} 18. b3 g6
$11) 18... Rfe8 19. b3 a5 20. Rae1 (20. Rad1 a4 $11) 20... Be5 21. Kh1 g6 22.
Qg4 Ra7 23. f4 Bg7 24. Re2 a4 $11 {[%cal Ga7a3]}) 15... Nd4 {There are no more
tricks along the h1-a8 diagonal.} 16. Nxd4 (16. O-O {is risk-free, e. g.} Qb6
17. Nxd4 Qxd4 $11 {Efimenko - Gelfand, Douglas, 2019}) ({White is unlikely to
bear the mighty Nd4 for long, therefore} 16. Nxb4 {is not a serious bet, as
shown by} Rb8 (16... Qb6 17. Nc6 Nxc6 18. dxc6 Rac8 19. O-O Rxc6 20. b3 Rfc8
$11) 17. Nc6 ({in reply to} 17. a3 {Black can cover the c6-outpost by} Qd7 $11
{and chase Nb4 under the most favourable conditions}) 17... Nxc6 18. dxc6 Qa5+
19. Qd2 Qxd2+ 20. Kxd2 Rfc8 $11 21. Rhc1 $2 Bg5+) 16... exd4 17. Qd3 {[%csl
Gd4] A reasonable try to block the d4-pawn and ?f6, respectively.} ({The
artificial} 17. Bf1 {is naturally met by} d3) (17. O-O d3 $1 {[%cal Gf6b2]} 18.
Qb3 (18. Rb1 Qa5) 18... Rc8 19. Rad1 Rc2 20. Qxd3 Qc8 (20... Rxb2 21. Qxa6 Bc3
$11) 21. Rd2 $6 (21. Bh3 $1 {was obligatory, with the idea to deflect ?c8 from
the a6-pawn; if Black still objects its exchange for the one on b2, then} Qc4 {
is an easy equalizer -} 22. Qxc4 Rxc4 23. Rd2 Rxe4 24. Rc1 $11) 21... Rxb2 22.
Rxb2 Bxb2 $15 23. Qb3 Bc3 24. a3 a5 25. axb4 axb4 {After missing his best
opportunity to clarify the situation on the queenside, White has been saddled
in an unpleasant (mostly from a psychological point of view) position, in
which he is practically a pawn down. No wonder he cracked at the  first
attempt to display activity -} 26. Rc1 Qc5 27. Rc2 Qd4 28. Ra2 g6 29. h4 h5 30.
Bf3 Rc8 31. Kg2 Kg7 32. Ra6 $2 Be1 $1 33. Ra2 Rc1 34. Re2 Qc3 $19 35. Re3 Qxb3
36. Rxb3 Rc2 37. Kf1 Bxf2 38. e5 Rc3 {0-1 Balogh - Cheparinov, Patras, 2019.})
17... Rc8 $1 18. O-O (18. Bh3 Rc5 19. O-O Qc7 20. Qxa6 d3 21. Qxd3 Bxb2 22.
Rab1 Bc3 $132 {[%csl Ra2,Gc3,Re4][%cal Gf8a8]}) 18... Qc7 $1 19. Bh3 (19. Qxa6
d3 20. Qxd3 Bxb2 21. Rab1 Bc3 $11 {is quite similar to the previous note.})
19... Qc2 ({Black has consequently occupied the c-file and} 19... Qc4 20. Qd2
Qc2 21. Qxb4 Rc5 $44 {is keeping the rook on it, if he prefers. The text is
also leading to regaining the pawn and approximate equality.}) 20. Qxa6 Rcd8 {
[%csl Rb2,Re4]} 21. Rfd1 Qxe4 $11 *

