{[%evp 0,44,33,20,51,60,45,38,4,4,34,38,44,44,44,6,6,6,6,18,18,6,6,6,3,0,8,19,
24,11,36,21,12,14,19,27,35,25,28,34,39,42,50,15,16,23,24]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10.
Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 O-O 12. Nc2 Rb8 $5 (12... Bg5 13. a4 bxa4 14. Rxa4 a5 15. Bc4
{is the old main theretical line, which is far from being refuted, but it
makes sense to take immediate measures against the intended a2-a4 break.
Moreover, Magnus Carlsen is fond of this move order.}) 13. h4 $5 (13. Be2 Bg5
14. O-O Kh8 $5 ({Black has plenty of continuations to choose from -} 14... a5)
(14... Be6 15. Qd3 g6) ({or} 14... g6 {, but the text move is both useful and
flexible while keeping all the mentioned alternatives open:}) 15. Qd3 (15. Bg4
Bb7 $1 (15... Be6 $6 16. Ndb4 Nxb4 17. Nxb4 Rb6 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. Qg4 $14) 16.
Qd3 (16. Ncb4 Nxb4 17. cxb4 {can hardly pretend for much -} g6 18. a4 bxa4 19.
Rxa4 Bc6 $11 {Giri - Carlsen, Wijk aan Zee, 2019}) (16. Nce3 {is typically
answered by} Ne7) ({as well as} 16. a4 Ne7) 16... Ne7 17. Nxe7 ({White's
control over the d5-outpost is very shaky - after} 17. Nce3 {there is a
pleasant choice between exchanging this knight and} Nxd5 18. Nxd5 g6) 17...
Qxe7 18. Nb4 g6 19. Rad1 (19. Nd5 Qd8 {transposes to the previous note}) 19...
h5 20. Be2 Kg7 $11 {[%csl Re4]}) (15. a4 bxa4 16. Ncb4 {White is back to this
ambitious plan after having his king evacuated, after} Nxb4 {both ways to
recapture are worth considering:} 17. Nxb4 (17. cxb4 {is the more demanding of
them:} Bd7 (17... f5 18. exf5 (18. Rxa4 fxe4 19. Bxa6 Be6 $132) 18... Bd7 19.
Bxa6 Rxf5 20. Bd3 Rf8 $11) 18. Bxa6 Bc6 (18... Qe8 19. Nc7 {may result in a
repetition}) 19. Bc4 {a rather safe continuation is} (19. Rxa4 Bxa4 20. Qxa4 f5
21. Bd3 fxe4 22. Bxe4 Qc8 $132) (19. b5 Bxb5 20. Bxb5 Rxb5 21. Qxa4 Rxb2 $11)
19... Bxd5 ({indeed,} 19... f5 {is a fighting option, albeit far from being an
obligatory one -} 20. exf5 Qc8 21. b3 (21. b5 Bxb5 22. Bxb5 Rxb5 23. Rxa4 Qxf5
