{In this lecture, I will show you the most typical ideas in the variation
after 10.Nd5. It is a positional line, where White wants to stay solid. First
I will show you the best scenarios for White and the positions you should
avoid with Black. The first example is the masterpiece of Garry Kasparov
against Alexei Shirov.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6.
Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 a6 9. Na3 b5 10. Nd5 Be7 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 {With a
slightly unusual move order we reach the main tabya of Sveshnikov Variation.
White has full control of the d5-square but gives up his bishop pair. Also
Black has a worse pawn structure, the d6-pawn is a weakness and the queenside
pawns could become a target after the a2-a4 break. Nevertheless, the practice
shows that Black has enough compensation for the weaknesses and the "d5"
square. White's a3-knight is misplaced and will take some time to activate.
Black's main idea is based on the break f7-f5, also very often Black seeks
counterplay on the b-file.} 12. c3 {White is preparing the maneuvre: Na3-c2-e3}
(12. c4 {Is another idea for White, which we will see in some of the next
examples.}) 12... Bb7 {The idea is to follow with the maneuvre Nb8-d7. This
move is considered inaccurate nowadays. The practice shows that Black should
keep his lightsquared bishop on "c8" as long as possible, because it is not
clear where this bishop belongs.} 13. Nc2 Nb8 {Black's idea is Nd7 followed by
Nc5 or Nb6, depending on the circumstances.} 14. a4 $1 {Kasparov delays the
development of the kingside and employs one of White's main strategy was to
undermine the structure on the kingside.} bxa4 15. Rxa4 Nd7 16. Rb4 $1 Nc5 (
16... Bc6 {will be well met by} 17. Rc4 $16) (16... Rb8 {Later, it was
discovered that this is the best reaction for Black.}) 17. Rxb7 $3 {Brilliant
positional exchange sacrifice. Kasparov now obtained full control of the light
squares and the chance to create a passed pawn on the queenside by b4, c4, b5.
In my opinion the outcome of the game is already decided here. White has a
straightforward play and a clear way to improve his position. In the meantime,
Black has no counterplay.} Nxb7 18. b4 {Restricting the knight and preparing b5
} Bg5 19. Na3 {Before starting any concrete actions, Kasparov activates his
knight} O-O 20. Nc4 a5 {With this move Shirov helps White to create a passed
pawn on the queenside. On the other hand , understandably, Shirov is trying to
get at least some counterplay on the "a" file} 21. Bd3 axb4 22. cxb4 Qb8 23. h4
Bh6 24. Ncb6 Ra2 25. O-O {[%cal Rb6d7] Nd7 is quite a nasty threat.} Rd2 26.
Qf3 Qa7 27. Nd7 Nd8 28. Nxf8 Kxf8 29. b5 {With equal material, the game's
outcome is crystal clear. White dominates all over the board. The rest is a
simple technique.} Qa3 30. Qf5 Ke8 31. Bc4 Rc2 32. Qxh7 Rxc4 33. Qg8+ Kd7 34.
Nb6+ Ke7 35. Nxc4 Qc5 36. Ra1 Qd4 37. Ra3 Bc1 38. Ne3 1-0

