{GM Vasil Spasov is a famous Bulgarian GM, former World Champion U20 and a
very strong positional player. He has played Sveshnikov all his life with both
colors, and I can advise everyone to take a look at his games because he
understands the arising positions and structures very well.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 a6 9. Na3 b5 10.
Nd5 Be7 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. c3 Bb7 13. Nc2 Nb8 14. a4 bxa4 15. Rxa4 Nd7 {The
first fifteen moves were the same as in the previous game. Now White chooses a
different plan.} 16. Ra2 {For some reason Spasov deviates from Kasparov's game.
I am 99% sure that both players were familiar with it and Black had some
improvement in mind.} O-O 17. Bc4 {The rule in this structure is that if
White's bishop reaches the c4-square in one move and is doing fine.} Bg5 18.
O-O a5 19. Qe2 Nb6 20. Nxb6 Qxb6 21. Rd1 Kh8 22. Ra3 {Nice regrouping. White
is planning Rb3 followed by Na3-b5.} Rab8 23. Rb3 Qc7 24. Na3 Bc6 25. Nb5 Bxb5
26. Rxb5 Rxb5 27. Bxb5 {We all know that the positions with Whites knight
against the dark-squared bishop are favorable for White, and there are many
classical examples. In this example, we will see that the weakness of the
d5-square could be critical even in positions with opposite-colored bishops.
We should be aware of the enormous attacking potential of the positions with
opposite coloured bishops. The attacking possibilities are considerably higher
if one of the sides has weakened squares in his camp. In the structures with
weakness on d5, White light-squared bishop could be powerful if some major
pieces support it. After maneuvering play, many exchanges reached the critical
position of the game. Some inexperienced players can agree to a draw here,
because of the opposite-colored bishops and the reduced material, but for a
trained eye is obvious that White has a huge advantage. His bishop will be
transferred to a2-g8 - diagonal and will dominate the entire board. Black has
weaknesses - "a5", "d6". White's plan is similar to the positions when White
has a knight on d5. 1. Improve the position of all our pieces. 2. Start making
weaknesses on the kingside. 3.Put pressure on weak pawns - "a5" and "d6" 4.
Combine an attack against the weaknesses with an attack against the king and
finally invade the opponent's camp.} Rb8 28. g3 g6 {This move creates new
weaknesses on the kingside. The main problem for Black is that his
dark-squared bishop is very passive. Had his bishop been on the a7-g1 -
diagonal, the assessment would have been completely different. For example,
with a bishop on c5, Black could have created some threats on the kingside by
means of Rf8 followed by f7-f5.} 29. Bc4 Kg7 30. b3 $1 {Another important
positional move. By overprotecting his bishop, White reduces the activity of
his opponent's rook.} Rb6 31. h4 $1 {Of course, as always in this kind of
structure, it is highly advantageous to weaken the opponent's kingside
structure further.} Bd8 32. Ra1 Rc6 33. h5 $1 Bg5 (33... g5 $2 {was a
positional suicide as Black not only weakens the light-squares in his camp but
at the same time he closes his bishop.}) 34. Kg2 Rc5 35. Qf3 Qe7 36. Bd5 Qc7
37. Qg4 Bd2 38. hxg6 hxg6 39. Rh1 {Finally White starts the attack against the
Black king. Black is hopeless against the numerous threats.} Qc8 40. Qh4 Rc7
41. Qh7+ Kf6 42. Rd1 $1 {White's rook is coming on f3} Bf4 43. Rd3 (43. gxf4 $2
Qg4+ $19) 43... Qg4 44. Qh8+ Ke7 45. Qg8 Rd7 46. Qxf7+ Kd8 47. Qg8+ Ke7 48. Be6
Qe2 49. Bxd7 Qxe4+ 50. Rf3 Kxd7 51. Qf7+ Kc6 52. gxf4 {Wonderful game which
shows the potential of White's position.} 1-0

