{[%evp 0,123,25,15,50,49,49,49,39,26,26,42,44,62,54,-5,-6,-13,27,5,4,3,3,-8,28,
21,8,-2,14,-5,15,12,10,11,6,1,26,-1,-10,-25,-14,-2,13,16,16,15,38,-30,12,31,31,
16,27,30,26,29,17,0,2,6,11,10,16,18,18,19,18,25,102,114,112,109,107,95,88,91,
93,89,93,69,108,81,87,105,112,123,123,126,131,127,127,133,146,143,133,133,133,
115,168,168,186,73,85,97,122,119,140,133,133,158,197,189,195,202,232,232,232,
274,273,230,261,298,334,352,336,560] Another idea which I can't recommend for
Black is the early Ne7. I will show you a few games of Magnus Carlsen here. We
should note that they were played 15 years ago and Magnus still wasn't that
strong. Nowadays, he is definitely the biggest specialist of Svestnikov and
you should follow all his games.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5.
Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 Bg5 12.
Nc2 Ne7 $6 {Looks logical, Black is trying to fight for the d5-square.
Unfortunately, it is not enough for equality.} (12... Rb8 $1 {I prefer this
move here, but it will be discussed in the later example.}) 13. h4 $1 {Very
precise reaction, White forces Black's bishop to the h6-square. There the
bishop is quite passive and very far from his dream position at "a7-g1"
diagonal.} Bh6 14. a4 $1 {As we already know, White's main strategical idea is
to make progress on the queenside.} bxa4 15. Ncb4 $1 {White's second knight is
ready to occupy the d5-square.} O-O 16. Qxa4 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 a5 18. Bb5 Be6 19.
Bc6 Rb8 20. b4 Bxd5 {strategical collapse. As we know from the game Spasov -
Halkias, this position is always quite unpleasant for Black.} (20... axb4 21.
cxb4 Kh8 {[%cal Rf7f5] is more of the spirit of the position, but White is
still better after} 22. b5) 21. Bxd5 axb4 22. cxb4 Qb6 23. Rb1 Kh8 24. O-O f5
25. Qa5 (25. b5 $1 {I can't see why Leko decided to exchange the queens.
Probably he was afraid of some counterplay against the f2-pawn.}) 25... fxe4
26. Qxb6 Rxb6 27. Rb3 Rc8 28. Ra1 g6 29. Ra8 {Leaving Black without any
dynamic changes.} Rxa8 30. Bxa8 Bf8 31. b5 Be7 32. g3 Bd8 33. Bxe4 d5 {this is
unnecessary} ({Black should be able to hold the game after:} 33... Rb8 {
[%cal Rd8b6,Rb6c5,Rh8g7]}) 34. Bxd5 Rd6 35. Bc6 Bb6 36. Rb2 Rd3 37. Kg2 Kg7 38.
Be4 Ra3 39. g4 Bd4 40. Rc2 Rb3 41. Rc7+ Kh8 42. Rc8+ Kg7 43. Rc7+ Kh8 44. Rb7
Rb2 45. h5 Rxf2+ 46. Kg3 Rf4 $2 (46... gxh5 47. gxh5 Rf6 48. Rxh7+ Kg8 49. Rd7
$16 {Of course, Black is much worse, but still keep some drawing chances.}) 47.
h6 $1 {Now Black's king is in danger and the b-pawn is dangerously close to
promotion.} Rf8 48. Rc7 Bf2+ 49. Kg2 Be3 50. g5 Rb8 51. Rc3 Bd4 52. Rc6 Kg8 53.
Bd5+ Kf8 54. Bc4 Ke7 55. Rc7+ Kd6 56. Rxh7 e4 57. Rg7 Kc5 58. Rc7+ Kd6 59. Rc6+
Ke5 60. Rxg6 Kf5 61. Rd6 Be3 62. h7 1-0

