1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 Bg5 12. Nc2 Ne7 13. Ncb4 (13. h4 {
was in the Leko - Carlsen}) 13... O-O 14. a4 bxa4 15. Qxa4 a5 16. Bb5 Nxd5 17.
Nxd5 {Now, we have a very similar position to the previous game. The
difference is that Black's bishop is still on "g5" and can be transferred to
a1-g7 diagonal easy. We can see that even here, Black is quite far from
equality} Be6 {The bishop is better placed here than on "b7", because it also
supports the f7-f5 break.} 18. Bc6 Rb8 19. Ra2 Qc8 {freeing the d8-square.} 20.
O-O Bd8 21. b4 {White proceeds with his main plan: to create a passed pawn on
the "b" file.} Kh8 (21... f5 $2 {is not working with the king on "g8", because
of} 22. exf5 Bxf5 23. bxa5 $18 Bxa5 $4 24. Ne7+) 22. Rd2 Qa6 $6 {is just bad} (
22... f5 {Black needs to start his counterplay.}) 23. b5 Qa7 24. Qa3 {Now we
can see that the d6-pawn is very weak.} Bxd5 25. Qxd6 $1 $18 {This was a blitz
game, so it is understandable why Carlsen missed such a simple tactic.} Be7 26.
Qxd5 Rfd8 27. Qa2 Rxd2 28. Qxd2 a4 29. Qa2 a3 30. Qxf7 Rf8 31. b6 $1 1-0

