35,32,32,21,31,15,15,7,-14]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 Ne7 {This is
a trendy attempt at the Ne7 idea. Black is playing without losing time for Bg5.
In my opinion, this move doesn't equalize.} 12. Nc2 {Probably Giri was
surprised by Magnus' choice and chose a drawish line} (12. Nxf6+ $1 {This is
the correct approach. Black will have long-term weaknesses} gxf6 13. Bd3 d5 {
Even if Black manages to push d5 or f5, his pawn structure remains worse.} 14.
Qe2 {I am providing you with a few illustrative lines which show the danger of
Black's position.} Bb7 (14... dxe4 15. Bxe4 Rb8 16. O-O f5 17. Rad1 (17. Bc2
Qc7 18. Rae1 Ng6 19. Qh5 $16) 17... Qc7 18. Bb1) 15. O-O-O Qb6 16. Nc2 O-O-O
17. exd5 Bxd5 18. Nb4 Bb7 (18... Be6 $2 19. Qf3 $1 $16) 19. Be4 $14) 12... Nxd5
13. Qxd5 Rb8 14. Nb4 Bb7 15. Qd3 O-O 16. Be2 a5 17. Nd5 b4 $1 {is a very
typical way of creating counterplay. Black is making weaknesses on the
queenside, compensating for the weak d5-square.} 18. O-O bxc3 19. bxc3 Bg5 20.
Rab1 Qd7 21. Rb3 Bc6 22. Rfb1 Rxb3 23. Rxb3 g6 24. Rb6 Rc8 25. h3 Bxd5 {
This wasn't even necessary.} (25... h5 $5) (25... Qd8 $5) 26. Qxd5 Rxc3 27.
Rxd6 Qe7 28. Bd1 Rc7 29. g3 Kg7 30. Ba4 Bc1 31. Rc6 1/2-1/2

