1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 {This move became popular recently, but
I always find it completely harmless for Black. It gives Black access to the
d4-square and keeps the queenside closed.} b4 12. Nc2 O-O 13. g3 a5 {This is
the classical way to continue. Black is defending the b4-pawn and is ready to
continue with the maneuver Nb8-d7(a6)-c5} 14. Bg2 Bg5 15. O-O Be6 16. Qd3 Bxd5
{This is only one of the possible plans.} (16... Qb8 {With the idea to free
the d8-square for the bishop and to support a4-b3 looks quite ambitious} 17. f4
Bd8 18. Kh1 a4) (16... Ne7 {Again, the standard Nc6-e7 maneuver deserves
attention.}) 17. cxd5 (17. Qxd5 Qb6 {[%cal Ra5a4,Rb4b3]}) 17... Nb8 18. a3 Na6
19. axb4 Nxb4 20. Nxb4 axb4 {Now the position becomes too dry} 21. h4 Bh6 22.
Bh3 {This is another typical idea that you should know. White is taking
control over the c8-square and transfers the bishop to c6-square} Qb6 23. Bd7
b3 24. Bc6 Ra2 {Black took the initiative, and White should consider equalizing
} 25. Rxa2 bxa2 26. Qa3 Rb8 27. Qxa2 {and the draw was aggreed} 1/2-1/2

