{GM Nedev has been my teammate on the Macedonian National Team for many years.
He is an outstanding theoretician and has played Sveshnikov all his life.} 1.
e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3
b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 b4 12. Nc2 O-O 13. g3 {The moves so far are
the same as in the previous game. But here, GM Nedev employs a very
interesting idea, which I quite like Black. He transfers the queen to "c5"
before playing a5.} Bg5 14. Bg2 Qa5 $5 {It looks logical to use this square to
transfer the queen to a better position.} 15. O-O Qc5 16. b3 a5 17. Qd3 Ra7 $1
{Another important idea for Black. The rook is usually very useful on the 7th
rank} 18. Kh1 f5 (18... Ne7 $5 {With the idea to exchange on d5 looks quite
good.}) 19. f4 Bh6 20. Rad1 g6 21. Nde3 exf4 22. gxf4 fxe4 23. Bxe4 Ne7 {
The weakness of the d6-pawn is compensated by the weakness of the f4-pawn.} 24.
Nd5 Nxd5 25. Bxd5+ Kh8 {very typical situation for Svestnikov. The king on h8
is very safe, because White doesn't have a dark-squared bishop} 26. Nd4 Re7 27.
f5 Bxf5 28. Nxf5 gxf5 29. Rxf5 Qe3 30. Rxf8+ Bxf8 31. Qf5 Bg7 32. Rg1 h6 33.
Qc8+ Re8 34. Qd7 $4 {a blunder in a timetrouble} (34. Qg4 Qe5 $11) 34... Qe7 (
34... Bd4 $1 35. Rf1 Rg8 $19) 35. Qf5 Bd4 36. Rf1 Qg7 37. Qf3 Re5 38. Bf7 Rg5
39. Qa8+ Kh7 40. Qe4+ Kh8 41. Qe8+ Kh7 42. Qe1 h5 43. Bd5 Qe5 44. Qb1+ Kh6 45.
Re1 Qf4 46. Rf1 Qe3 47. Re1 Qf4 48. Rf1 Qe3 1/2-1/2

