{[%evp 0,100,23,10,48,59,59,22,22,22,41,41,52,29,29,3,0,0,4,4,4,3,3,3,12,11,20,
20,20,5,19,7,7,6,21,10,16,28,25,21,25,25,26,13,13,20,0,19,25,35,36,18,18,29,29,
0,0,0,0,-20,44,-11,-11,-17,-21,-21,-24,-159,-97,-97,-97,-174,-156,-505,-243,
-237,-245,-249,-257,-259,-259,-258,-258,-243,-168,-225,-233,-252,-274,-266,
-266,-248,-248,-248,-246,-246,-248,-262,-242,-500,-504,-544,-549]} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5
Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 Bg5 12. Nc2 O-O 13. a4 bxa4 14. Rxa4 a5 15. Bc4 {
This was one of the main tabyas in Sveshnikov for many years} Rb8 {[%csl Rc8]
delaying the decision to develop the bishop} 16. Ra2 (16. b3 {is the more
common way to defend the pawn}) 16... Kh8 17. Nce3 Bxe3 $5 {Remember this
exchange. Black is exchanging his worst piece. My advice is if you can
exchange it, do it} 18. Nxe3 Ne7 $1 {Only now. We are controlling the
d5-square and we will be happy to exchange the knights.} 19. b3 f5 20. exf5
Nxf5 21. Nd5 Bb7 22. O-O Rc8 23. Qd3 Nh4 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Rb7g2,Rh4g2] Black
still has worse pawn structure. He is trying to compensate it by seeking
dynamic chances on the kingside. We can conclude that the position is balanced.
} 24. Rd1 h6 25. Qg3 (25. Rad2 {can be met by the very strong:} a4 $1 26. b4 $4
(26. bxa4 $4 Rxc4 27. Qxc4 Qg5 $19) (26. Qg3 $1 {is keeping the balance}) 26...
Qg5 {and Black wins}) 25... Nf5 26. Qg4 Rc5 27. Rad2 Bc8 28. Qe4 Bb7 29. h3 {
Karjakin decided to play for a win} Nh4 30. Bd3 Rf5 31. Bb1 Rxc3 $1 32. Qg4 (
32. Rd3 $1 Rc5 33. R3d2 Rc3 $11) 32... h5 33. Qe2 Qg5 {All Black's pieces are
taking part in the attack.} 34. f4 Rxf4 35. Kh1 Nxg2 {Topalov ended the game
in a style} 36. Qxg2 Rg3 (36... Qh4 $1 $19 {is even more convincing}) 37. Nxf4
Bxg2+ 38. Nxg2 Rxh3+ 39. Kg1 Rg3 $19 40. Rf2 Kg8 41. Rxd6 h4 42. Rc6 Qg4 43.
Bf5 Rxg2+ 44. Rxg2 Qxf5 45. Rcg6 Qf7 46. R6g4 Qf6 47. Kh2 Kf7 48. Kh3 e4 49.
Rg5 e3 50. Kxh4 g6 0-1

