{[%evp 0,101,19,31,72,53,33,26,42,18,25,31,51,55,43,-7,-7,-10,-3,-7,-8,-8,-8,
-14,3,-1,25,-10,-10,-19,46,-9,11,-12,42,7,27,-4,34,17,38,-9,16,12,12,0,49,-22,
-21,-12,16,-2,73,-28,-2,-8,8,-36,-4,-9,41,35,35,37,114,-34,67,77,94,97,122,92,
106,157,215,300,268,353,368,260,259,252,260,274,271,273,273,281,392,281,281,
277,270,223,268,262,277,246,419,638,893,1327,1684,2227]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10.
Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 O-O 12. Nc2 Rb8 {I quite like the idea of Rb8, but I don't
think that this move order is accurate} 13. h4 $1 {keeping the bishop passive}
Be7 (13... g6 {Magnus Carlsen tried this in a couple of games and proved that
Black is doing fine here. Still, I believe that White's play is easier}) 14.
Nce3 {Now the knight can easily come to e3, without worrying that Black can
exchange his bad bishop for it.} Be6 15. Qf3 $5 {This is an interesting plan.
Instead of the more typical 15.a4, White decides to finish the development and
combine an attack on the kingside and an attack against the weak d6-pawn.} Qd7
16. Rd1 Bd8 17. Be2 Ne7 18. h5 h6 {forced necessity. Black can't allow White's
pawn to reach h6} 19. O-O Bb6 $6 (19... Qc8 {Is the main theoretical move with
the idea to free the d7-square for the bishop} 20. Nxe7+ Bxe7 21. Nf5 Qc7 {
leads to more or less balanced game}) 20. Nf5 Bxf5 21. exf5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 {
This is exactly the position which Black should avoid} Qe7 23. Bd3 Rfd8 24. Rd1
Rbc8 25. Be4 $18 {White is strategically winning and easily converts his
advantage.} Rc4 26. Re1 Rc5 27. a3 a5 28. b4 axb4 29. axb4 Rxd5 30. Bxd5 Rc8
31. Ra1 Qg5 32. g3 e4 33. Bxe4 Qf6 34. Ra3 Qe5 35. Kg2 Bd8 36. Bd5 Bf6 37.
Bxf7+ Kh8 38. Ra8 Rd8 39. Qc6 Qe7 40. Be6 Qf8 41. Rxd8 Qxd8 42. Qxb5 Bxc3 43.
Qc4 Bd2 44. Qd4 Bg5 45. b5 Qb8 46. Bc4 Bd8 47. Qe4 Bb6 48. Qe7 Bd4 49. Bd5 Kh7
50. Qf7 Qd8 51. b6 1-0

