1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 {This is the last trend and maybe
the most precise way for Black to equalize. I like it because it limits
White's options.} 12. Nc2 (12. h4 $2 {doesn't make any sense here, because
Black can take the pawn}) 12... Bg5 {We delayed castling for two moves, but
White can't use this in his favour} 13. g3 (13. a3 {This is an interesting
move which Wesley So and Shankland tried recently} O-O (13... Ne7 {Is an
interesting alternative, tried by Vladimir Kramnik against Kasparov} 14. Nxe7 (
14. Ncb4 {was an interesting alternative:} Nxd5 15. Nxd5 (15. exd5 Qb6 16. a4
O-O 17. axb5 axb5 18. g3 e4 {1/2 (25)-1/2 Lanka,Z-Jelen, I/Ljubljana 1994 (31)}
) 15... O-O 16. Bd3 $5 Be6 17. Bc2) 14... Qxe7 $1 {1/2 (97)-1/2 (97) Polgar,J 
(2700) -Kramnik,V (2807) Wijk aan Zee 2003 CBM 093}) (13... a5 {Kramnik tried
to insist for b5-b4 break, but failed to equalize in the game:} 14. Bd3 Ne7 15.
Nxe7 Qxe7 16. Qe2 O-O 17. O-O Bd7 18. b4 axb4 19. Nxb4 Rfc8 20. c4 $14 {
1/2-1/2 Kasparov, G-Kramnik,V/Frankfurt (rapid) 2000 (35)}) 14. h4 Bh6 15. g4
Bf4 {I like this position for Black. White is somewhat overextended and Black
has a lot of tactical possibilities.} 16. Qf3 Be6 (16... Bb7 {I prefer 16...
Be6, but Jeffrey played quite interesting and get a good position} 17. g5 Re8
18. Nxf4 exf4 19. O-O-O b4 20. axb4 Nxb4 21. Nxb4 Bxe4 22. Qxf4 Rxb4 23. Bd3
Bxh1 24. Qxb4 Bf3 $11 {1-0 (52) So,W (2770) -Xiong,J (2709) Lichess.org INT
2020}) 17. Nxf4 Qf6 {remember this idea} (17... exf4 {is possible too} 18. Qxf4
a5 $44) 18. g5 Qxf4 19. Qxf4 exf4 20. Nb4 Nxb4 21. axb4 $14 {Mamedyarov didn't
fully equalize but manages to make a draw 1/2 (55)-1/2 (56) So,W (2778)
-Mamedyarov,S (2762) chess24.com INT 2021}) (13. a4 bxa4 14. Ncb4 Nxb4 15. Nxb4
(15. cxb4 O-O 16. Rxa4 a5 {I prefer to keep the light square bishop at its
initial place as much as possible} 17. h4 Bh6 18. b5 Bd7 (18... Kh8 19. Be2 Be6
20. b4 axb4 21. Nxb4 Bd7 $11 {½- (84) ½ (84) Dominguez Perez,L (2758)
-Radjabov,T (2765) chess24.com INT 2021}) 19. Nc3 d5 $1 20. exd5 e4 $1 {
very nice play all over the board. The material doesn't really matter here.
Black's bishop pair fully compensate it} 21. Be2 e3 22. f4 g6 23. h5 Bg7 (23...
g5 $1) 24. h6 Bh8 25. d6 Rb6 26. Rxa5 $14 {1-0 (47) Dominguez Perez,L (2758)
-Xiong,J (2709) Lichess. org INT 2020}) 15... Bd7 {this move leads to more or
less forced draw after:} 16. Bxa6 Qa5 17. Qxd6 Rb6 18. Qd3 Be6 19. O-O Be7 20.
Bc4 Bxb4 21. Bxe6 Rxe6 22. cxb4 Qxb4 23. Qc2 O-O 24. Rxa4 Qb7 $11 {1/2 (43)-1/
2 (43) Grischuk,A (2775)-Caruana,F (2819) Stavanger 2019}) 13... O-O 14. Bg2 (
14. h4 Bh6 15. g4 (15. Bh3 Bb7 (15... Be6 $5) 16. O-O a5 (16... Ne7 {looks
very logical here} 17. Ncb4 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 g6 19. Qd3 f5 20. Rad1 (20. exf5 gxf5
21. Bxf5 (21. f4 Kh8 $15) (21. Rad1 f4 22. Qe2 Qe8 $15) 21... Rxf5 22. Qxf5
Bxd5 $17) 20... f4 {Black has very good attacking chances})) 15... Bf4 16. Qf3
Be6 17. Nxf4 exf4 18. Qxf4 b4 {white King is to weak. Black should be better})
14... a5 15. O-O Ne7 16. Nce3 (16. f4 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Be6 18. Qd2 Bh6 $15 {
0-1 (50) Andreikin,D (2400) -Carlsen,M (2385) Budva 2003}) 16... Be6 (16...
Bxe3 $5 17. Nxe3 Be6 18. Qd2 Qb6 $11) 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. Nf5 Qd8 19. Qxd6 g6
20. Qxd8 Rfxd8 21. h4 Bf6 22. Ne3 Rd2 23. b3 a4 {Black has a tremendous
compensation for the sacrificing pawn} 24. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 axb3 26. axb3
Bxb3 27. Rb1 Ba2 28. Rb2 Be6 29. Bf3 Be7 (29... Bd7 {is the safest choice}) 30.
Bg4 Bxg4 31. Nxg4 b4 32. cxb4 Rb5 33. h5 Rxb4 34. Rxb4 Bxb4 35. hxg6 hxg6 36.
Nxe5 Bc3 37. Nd3 f5 38. f3 Kf7 39. Kg2 Kf6 40. g4 Bd4 41. Kg3 Be3 42. Nb2 Kg5
