{[%evp 0,17,18,18,56,56,43,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,64,36]} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 {Perhaps it should
be called the new main variant, although I prefer the name "Kholmov's
variation". So, after 7.Nd5 Black has no choice: he has to take the knight,
and naturally, White takes the pawn. This pawn structure has become very
important in the 21st century in various variations of the Sicilian Defense.
White refuses to use the d5-square with his pieces, and by means of an
exchange, he moves the pawn there and strives for a pawn offensive on the
queenside} Nxd5 8. exd5 {Black has to make an important choice: where to
retreat with his knight, to b8 or to e7. In general terms, the knight's
retreat to e7 is more aggressive, but, on the other hand, Black is required to
be more precise because further on, with minimal inaccuracy, one can easily
not get out of the opening. The move to b8 is more accurate and more classic,
and it's harder not to get out of the opening here, but on the other hand,
it's a little more difficult to get active counterplay. One way or another,
this choice is primarily a matter of taste.} Nb8 {If we take the knight to b8,
then later it most often comes to d7. There is a possibility to activate it
further or by pushing the f&e pawns, providing the knight with an excellent e5
square. Also, depending on the situation, it can go to f6 or c5. It is
important that with d7 he slows down White's advance by controlling the
important c5-square, but at the same time blocks the way for the light-squared
bishop.} 9. c4 {This is the old main line but it's pretty unproblematic for
black at the moment.} (9. Be3 Be7 10. Qd2 a6 11. Na3 O-O (11... b5 $5 12. c4 (
12. Bd3 f5) 12... f5 $13 13. f4 O-O 14. cxb5 exf4 15. Bxf4 Nd7 16. Be2 Nc5 $44)
12. Nc4 Nd7 13. a4 (13. Be2 f5 14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 Nc5 $36) 13... f5 14. f3 {
- 9.a4}) (9. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3c3] This is just a tricky line. Nevertheless, it
was also encountered by strong chess players, though mostly with short control.
} a6 (9... Be7 $6 10. Qc3 {This is the point!} Na6 11. Be3 $36) 10. Qa3 Be7 (
10... b6 11. Bg5 $1 f6 (11... Be7 12. Bxe7 Kxe7 13. O-O-O $16 {So - Carlsen,
chess24.com rapid 2020}) 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. Nc3 $14) 11. Bg5 (11. Bd2 O-O 12. c4 (
12. Bb4 $6 axb5 13. Qxa8 Na6 14. Bd2 Bg5 $17 15. Qa7 Bxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Bf5) 12...
Nd7 $15) 11... Bf5 {Perhaps not the only but the easiest way to equalize.} (
11... Bxg5 12. Nxd6+ Kd7 13. Nxf7 Qf6 14. Nxh8 g6 15. Qh3+ $18) 12. Be2 (12.
Bxe7 Kxe7 13. c4 (13. f4 $2 Qb6 $1 (13... Nc6 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Qxd6+ Kxd6 16.
dxc6 Kxc6 17. fxe5 Rad8 $11) 14. fxe5 axb5 15. Qxa8 Na6 $1 16. Qxh8 Qe3+ 17.
Be2 Bg4 $19) 13... Qb6 14. Be2 Nd7 15. Nc3 a5 16. b3 Nc5 $132) 12... axb5 13.
Bxe7 Rxa3 14. Bxd8 Ra8 15. Bh4 (15. Bg5 f6 16. Be3 Ke7 17. Bxb5 Bxc2 18. Rc1
Ra5 $1 19. Bc4 Bf5 $11) 15... f6 16. Bxb5+ Ke7 17. Kd2 g5 18. Bg3 Rc8 19. c4
Nc6 $1 $44 {Either Black will win back the pawn or get sufficient compensation
for it. One way or another, opposite-colored bishops endgame will soon appear
on the board here, and the most probable result is a draw.}) 9... Be7 (9... a6
10. Qa4 (10. Nc3 Be7 11. Be2) 10... Nd7 (10... Bd7 11. Qa3 Bxb5 12. cxb5 $14)
11. c5 dxc5 (11... Rb8 12. Nxd6+ Bxd6 13. cxd6 O-O 14. Be2 b5 15. Qa3 $14) 12.
d6 axb5 13. Qxa8 Bxd6 (13... c4 $5) 14. Bxb5 O-O $13) (9... Nd7 10. Bd3 Be7 11.
O-O O-O 12. Qc2 $14) 10. Be2 {Wherever you develop the bishop, Black still has
quite sufficient counterplay. It is not so easy for White to achieve something,
he has to slow down the movement of the Black phalanx} (10. Bd3 a6 (10... O-O
11. O-O Bd7 12. a4 a5 13. c5 $1 dxc5 14. Qc2 $16) 11. Nc3 O-O 12. O-O f5 13. f3
(13. f4 Nd7 14. Kh1 g6 15. Be3 Bf6 16. Rc1 b6 17. b4 a5 18. a3 exf4 19. Bxf4
Be5 $132) (13. Kh1 e4 14. Be2 (14. Bc2 Nd7 15. Bf4 g5 16. Be3 Ne5 $36) 14...
Nd7 15. f4 exf3 16. Bxf3 Ne5 $132) 13... Nd7 14. a3 (14. Kh1 Bg5 15. b4 e4 $5 (
15... b6) 16. fxe4 (16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. fxe4 Ne5 18. Be2 f4 19. c5 Rf6 20. Qd2 {
Erigaisi - Mamedov,R France 2022} Bg4 $1 21. c6 Raf8 $1 22. cxb7 Qh5 $1 23.
Rxf4 Rxf4 24. Qxf4 Rxf4 25. b8=Q+ Rf8 26. Bxg4 Nxg4 27. Qxd6 Qh4 $44 28. Qg3 $2
Qf6 $19) 16... Bf6 $1 17. Bd2 Be5 18. Rxf5 Nf6 19. Rxe5 Ng4 $1 20. Bg5 Qb6 21.
Qd2 Nf2+ 22. Kg1 Nh3+ $11) 14... Bg5 15. Kh1 (15. b4 e4 $5 {The idea of
​​this positional sacrifice in one form or another is constantly in the
air in these lines.} 16. fxe4 Bf6 17. Bd2 Be5 $44) (15. Bxg5 Qxg5 16. Qc1 Qh4
$132) 15... b6 16. b4 Rb8 17. Rb1 (17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Qc1 Qh4 19. Qe3 g5 $132)
17... Bxc1 18. Qxc1 Qh4 $132) (10. Be3 O-O 11. Qd2 (11. Be2 a6 12. Nc3 f5 13.
f4 (13. f3 Bg5 14. Bf2 Nd7 $132 15. O-O Qf6 16. b4 Qh6 17. Qd3 $6 e4 18. fxe4
Ne5) 13... Nd7 14. O-O (14. Qd2 Bf6) 14... Bf6 15. Qd2 Re8 (15... exf4 16. Bxf4
Re8 $132) 16. Kh1 exf4 17. Bxf4 Ne5 $132) (11. Bd3 a6 12. Nc3 f5 13. f3 (13. f4
Nd7 14. O-O exf4 15. Bxf4 Ne5 $15) 13... Bg5 14. Bf2 Nd7 15. O-O Qf6 $132 {
[%cal Gf6h6,Gd7c5,Gd7f6]}) 11... f5 12. g3 (12. f3 Bh4+ 13. g3 f4 14. Bf2 Bg5
$36) (12. f4 Nd7 13. Be2 exf4 14. Bxf4 Nc5 15. O-O Ne4 16. Qc1 Bf6 $15) (12.
Bxa7 $6 Bg5 13. Qc3 Bd7 14. Bxb8 Bxb5 15. cxb5 Rxb8 16. Bc4 e4 $44) 12... Bd7
$5 13. O-O-O a6 14. Nc3 Be8 $5 15. Kb1 Nd7 $15) (10. c5 {There is an
opportunity to try to break through in the center immediately. But in fact,
this does not bring any tangible benefits to White} O-O (10... Na6 $5 11. cxd6
Bxd6 12. Bc4 Nc7 13. Nxd6+ Qxd6 14. O-O O-O) 11. Bc4 (11. Bd3 Na6 12. cxd6 Bxd6
13. O-O Nb4 14. Bb1 (14. Bc4 Bf5 $11) (14. Be4 f5 15. a3 fxe4 16. axb4 Bxb4 17.
d6 Kh8 $11) 14... Qd7 15. Qe2 b6 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Re1 Re8 18. Bf4 Bb7 19. Qe4
f5 $1 20. Bxe5 fxe4 21. Bxd6 Nd3 $11) (11. Be2 Na6 12. cxd6 Bxd6 13. O-O Nc7
14. Nxd6 Qxd6 $11) (11. Be3 Na6 12. cxd6 Bxd6 13. Bc4 Bb4+ 14. Nc3 Bf5 15. O-O
Rc8 $132) 11... Bd7 12. Nc3 (12. cxd6 Bxb5 13. dxe7 (13. Bxb5 Bxd6 14. O-O Nd7
$15) 13... Qxe7 14. Bxb5 Qb4+) 12... Qc7 {In order not to get worse after 13.
cxd6 Bxd6, White needs to sacrifice a pawn, and in this variation there is
some compensation, but just some. In this case, black can safely look to the
future} 13. Be3 dxc5 14. Ne4 Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Qb6 16. O-O Bf5 $13) 10... O-O 11.
O-O Nd7 (11... a6 12. Nc3 f5 13. f3 Nd7 14. a3 b6 (14... Bg5 15. b4 $14 e4 $6
16. fxe4 Bf6 17. Qe1 $16) 15. b4 $14 Bg5 16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. Qc1) (11... Bd7 $5
12. Nc3 (12. a4 a5 13. c5 $5 dxc5 14. Ra3 Na6 $13) 12... f5 13. a3 (13. Be3 a5
14. Qb3 Na6 $1 15. Qxb7 e4 $44) (13. f4 a5 14. Kh1 Bf6 $13) 13... Be8 (13... a5
14. Rb1 a4 15. Kh1 $14) 14. b4 a6 15. Be3 Nd7 16. Rc1 Bg5 $132) 12. a3 (12. Kh1
a6 13. Nc3 f5 14. f3 (14. f4 Bf6 15. Qc2 g6) 14... f4 $5 $146 {[%cal Ge7h4,
Gh4g3]} (14... Bg5 15. b4 b6 16. Na4 f4 $5 $13) 15. Ne4 Nf6 16. Bd3 Nxe4 17.
Bxe4 Bh4 $132) (12. Be3 a6 13. Nc3 f5 14. f3 (14. f4 Bf6 15. Qd2 exf4 16. Bxf4
