{[%evp 0,17,18,18,36,36,36,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29,29]} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7 {
After this retreat the knight won't stay there, because the kingside needs to
be developed. Its further path is to g6, which will support the pawns' advance
on the kingside. The knight's route to f5 hinders this goal a little, as it
blocks the path for the f-pawn. On g6 it seems to stand well, but there White
can disturb it with h2-h4-h5. There is also such a moment that it still moves
far away from the queenside and, accordingly, the knight cannot take part in
defensive actions on that part of the board where White is active. This, of
course, is a minus, but on the other hand, it is more active on the kingside.}
9. c4 (9. c3 {This move is not exactly in the spirit of position because White
has to be ready somewhere to move this pawn to c5, and the movement step by
step looks slow. However, there is a smart trap.} Nf5 ({After the natural} 9...
Ng6 $6 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Qb4 Qb8 12. Qc4 $16 {it turns out that the c4-square is
available for the queen. Black will have to play 12…Kd8 (an exchange on b5
is also a loss of castling), after which his position looks completely
unattractive.}) 10. a4 (10. Bd3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. c4 Bd7 13. Nc3 Nh4 $132)
10... Be7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O Bd7 {[%cal Gf5h4,Gf7f5,Ge7g5] Black is ready for
the standard kingside play - placing the knight on h4 the bishop on g5 and
moving the f-pawn. Another important resource for Black's counterplay is a6&b5}
(12... Nh4 13. f4 $36) 13. Kh1 {[%cal Gf2f4]} (13. f4 a6 (13... Qb6+ $6 14. Kh1
Ne3 15. a5 $1 $16) 14. Na3 g6 $1 15. Qf3 Rc8 $132) (13. c4 Nh4 14. Be3 (14. f4
a6 15. Nc3 exf4 16. Bxf4 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 Ng6 $13) 14... a6 15. Nc3 f5 16. f3 Bg5
17. Bf2 Ng6 $132) 13... a6 14. Na3 b5 15. axb5 axb5 16. Bd2 Bg5 $5 17. Bxg5
Qxg5 18. Bxb5 Nh4 19. Rg1 Rxa3 $1 20. Bxd7 Rxa1 21. Qxa1 Qd2 $132) (9. a4 {
With knight on e7 this is rare but also tricky} a6 {here the pluses of the
knight's position on e7 appear.} (9... Nf5 10. Bd3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. c4 $14)
(9... Ng6 10. Be3 a6 (10... Be7 11. a5) 11. Na3 $14) 10. Nc3 (10. Na3 $2 Qa5+
$17 {[%csl Gd5]}) 10... Ng6 (10... Nf5 11. Bd3 Be7 12. O-O $14) 11. g3 $5 (11.
a5 Be7 12. Bd2 (12. b4 O-O 13. Na4 f5 $36) 12... Bd7 (12... O-O 13. Na4 f5 14.
Nb6 Rb8 15. Qe2 $1 $36 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) (12... Bf5 13. Na4 Rc8 14. c4 O-O 15.
Ra3 $14) 13. Na4 Bxa4 14. Rxa4 f5 15. g3 e4 $132 {Despite the pair of white
bishops, black has ample counterplay.}) 11... Be7 (11... f5 12. h4 e4 13. Qd4
Ne5 14. Be2 Be7 15. a5 O-O 16. Be3 Bd7 17. Qb4 $14) 12. h4 O-O 13. h5 Nh8 14.
h6 (14. Be3 f5) (14. g4 Bg5 $15) 14... g6 15. Be3 f5 16. Qd2 Nf7 17. a5 Bd7
$132) 9... Ng6 (9... Nf5 10. Bd3 $14 {the game has a different character, but
White has better prospects. Still, the knight on f5 slightly slows down the
movement of the kingside pawns. If you drive away the white knight with a6 and
then put the knight on d4, then the knight is still unstable there}) 10. Qa4 (
10. Bd3 a6 11. Nc3 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Be3 f5 14. f3 Bg5 15. Bf2 Bd7 $36 {
[%cal Gd8f6,Gg6f4]}) (10. Be2 {in the case of a calm, accurate play, it just
turns out that here the knight on g6, of course, stands better than on d7. The
kingside pawns are ready to move and the knight on the kingside is already
actively placed.} a6 11. Nc3 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. a4 (13. Be3 Bg5 14. Qd2 Bxe3
15. fxe3 (15. Qxe3 f5 16. c5 f4 $5 17. Qd3 Nh4 18. Ne4 dxc5 19. d6 f3 20. Bxf3
Nxf3+ 21. gxf3 Bd7 $132) 15... b6 16. b4 a5 $13) 13... f5 (13... b6 14. b4 f5
15. a5 bxa5 16. Rxa5 Rb8 17. Ra4 e4 18. Qc2 Bf6 19. c5 Be5 20. g3 Qf6 21. Bd2
Nh4 $1 $132) (13... a5 14. Be3 b6 15. Qd2 f5 16. f3 $13) 14. a5 e4 15. f4 exf3
16. Bxf3 Ne5 17. Be2 b6 $132) (10. h4 Be7 (10... a6 11. Nc3 (11. h5 axb5 12.
hxg6 fxg6 13. cxb5 Be7 14. a4 O-O $132) 11... Nxh4 12. c5 Bd7 13. c6 bxc6 14.
Qa4 cxd5 $1 15. Qxh4 Qxh4 16. Rxh4 Bc6 $132) (10... h5 $6 11. g3 {the fact
that the white queen did not go to the queenside turns out to be completely in
White's favor. They are ready to bring the bishop to e2 and take it to h5 soon.
} Bg4 12. Qa4 $16 {the bishop has to be brought back and White has critical
variations with an extra tempo.}) 11. h5 (11. g3 e4 12. Be2 a6 13. Nd4 h6 $5
14. O-O O-O $132) (11. c5 a6 (11... O-O 12. h5 Nh4 13. h6 (13. cxd6 Bf6 14. h6
(14. Be3 $6 Bd7 $15) 14... g6 15. a4 (15. Bd2 e4 16. Bc3 Bxc3+ 17. Nxc3 Nf5
$132) 15... a6 16. Nc3 e4 17. Be2 e3 18. O-O Nf5 $132) 13... g6 14. Nxd6 Bxd6
15. cxd6 $36) 12. Nc3 (12. h5 axb5 13. hxg6 fxg6 14. Bxb5+ Bd7 $13) (12. cxd6
Bxd6 13. Nxd6+ Qxd6 14. h5 Ne7 15. h6 O-O $5 16. hxg7 Rd8 $132) 12... h5 13.
Qa4+ (13. g3 dxc5) 13... Kf8 14. cxd6 Qxd6 $13 15. g3) 11... Nh4 12. c5 (12. g3
Nf5) 12... Nf5 13. h6 g6 14. g4 a6 15. gxf5 axb5 16. Bxb5+ (16. fxg6 hxg6 17.
Bxb5+ Bd7 $132) 16... Bd7 17. Bxd7+ Qxd7 18. fxg6 hxg6 19. Qe2 (19. h7 dxc5 $13
) 19... Ra4 (19... O-O 20. h7+ Kh8 21. Bh6 Rfc8 22. Qf3 $16) 20. cxd6 Bxd6 $13)
(10. g3 Be7 11. Bg2 (11. h4 {- 10.h4}) 11... a6 12. Nc3 f5 $132) (10. c5 a6 11.
Nxd6+ Bxd6 12. cxd6 Qxd6 $15 {[%csl Gd5]}) 10... Bd7 11. Qb4 (11. Qa3 Bxb5 12.
cxb5 Be7 13. b6 O-O 14. bxa7 Bg5 $44) 11... Qb8 12. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gb4a5]} (12.
Be2 Be7 (12... a6 13. Nc3 Be7 14. a4 $14) 13. O-O (13. a4 O-O) 13... O-O 14. a4
(14. g3 Bh3 15. Re1 f5 $36) 14... b6 $5 15. a5 bxa5 16. Qxa5 Nf4 17. Bxf4 exf4
$132) 12... b6 (12... a6 13. Nc3 Be7 {then there is such a small but
unpleasant nuance for Black. Without including the moves h4 h5, the h4-pawn
does not hang and White does not need to waste a tempo on its defense.} (13...
a5 14. Qa3 (14. Qb3 a4 15. Qb4 Be7) 14... Be7 15. O-O-O O-O 16. Kb1) 14. Na4
Qc7 15. Qb6 (15. Bb6 Qc8 16. Ba5 Rb8 17. Nb6 Qc7 18. Na8 Qc8 19. Nc7+ Kf8 20.
c5 Kg8 $1 $36 21. cxd6 Bf8 22. Qb6 h5 $1 {[%cal Gh8h6]}) 15... Rc8 16. Qxc7
Rxc7 17. Nb6 $14 {White gets a dream endgame because, without queens, Black
can hardly organize a successful king attack. And White is ready to complete
the development gradually and prepare the c4-c5 step by step. The knight on b6
here is simply the master of the position on the board}) (12... Be7 $6 13. c5
$16) 13. h4 (13. g3 Be7 14. h4 h5 {- 13.h4}) (13. a4 Be7 14. Bd3 f5 15. O-O O-O
