1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 {The main goal of this move is to damage Black's pawn structure.
} ({By contrast, in the positional variation} 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 {
instead of damaging Black's kingside structure, White typically plans to get
the upper hand on the queenside with the quick c3, Nc2, a4, etc.} 11. c3 (11.
c4 $5 b4 12. Nc2 {[%csl Rd6] is a different approach altogether.}) 11... Bg5
12. Nc2 O-O ({Black cannot easily eliminate the d5-knight in this variation,
for example:} 12... Ne7 13. h4 $5 Bh6 14. a4 bxa4 15. Ncb4 {[%csl Yd5]}) {
Here is a sample line that shows White's main ideas in the positional
variation:} 13. a4 $1 bxa4 14. Rxa4 Kh8 15. Bc4 {[%csl Yc4,Yd5] This
solidifying move is almost never available to White in the dynamic 9.Bxf6 line;
he has no time for a2-a4 in most cases.} f5 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. O-O a5 18. Nce3
Be6 19. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Yf5,Rg7][%cal Yg7f5] White has a strong grip on
the light squares and Black counterplay in the center is not so dangerous
compared to 9.Bxf6 because his pawn is on g7 and not on f5. This is just a
line that allows us to compare and contrast 9.Bxf6 and 9.Nd5 variations; Black
has many resources to balance the game, of course.}) 9... gxf6 {Black has: 1.
a dynamic pawn center 2. bishop pair advantage 3. often has to be ready to
sacrifice a pawn or two to activate his assets White: 1. has a better pawn
structure 2. controls white-square complex 3. usually tries to capitalize on
the d5-square and the light squares} (9... Qxf6 $2 {preserves structural
integrity but fails tactically to} 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Bxb5 $1 {A very typical and,
often, dangerous motif in this variation. Here, it leads to a dominant
position for White after} axb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5+ 13. c3 Kd8 14. a4 $40 {[%csl Rd8]
[%cal Ge1g1,Gb2b4]}) 10. Nd5 Bg7 {[%cal Gc6e7] By overprotecting the f6-pawn,
Black prepares to exchange the powerful d5-knight with ...Ne7. I recommend
this move for the basis of the Sveshnikov repertoire because it leads to
simpler and more intuitive positions than the alternative 10...f5.} (10... f5 {
[%csl Re4] is a different approach. Instead of challenging the d5-knight,
Black decides to ignore it for the time being and fight for the control of the
e4-square at once. It usually leads to more complex play compared to 10...Bg7.}
11. Bd3 {This is the most popular move.} (11. c3 {[%cal Ga3c2] is another
common approach.} Bg7 (11... fxe4 $2 {is premature in the view of} 12. Bxb5 $1
axb5 13. Nxb5 Be6 14. Nbc7+ Kd7 15. Nxa8 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 $16) 12. exf5 Bxf5 13.
Nc2 O-O 14. Nce3 Be6 15. Bd3 f5 {[#] This is an important tabiya of the 9.Bxf6
variation. Since we also reach it from the 9...Bg7 10.c3 f5 11.exf5 move order,
we will study it in the 9...Bg7 variation.}) (11. g3 {has been somewhat
neglected in the past, but strong players have been giving it more attention
recently. After} fxe4 12. Bg2 Be6 13. Bxe4 Bg7 $1 14. Qh5 (14. Nf6+ $6 Bxf6 15.
Bxc6+ Ke7 16. Bxa8 Qxa8 $36) 14... Rc8 15. Rd1 {[#] Black cannot castle nor
play the thematic ...f5 easily. We have an interesting middlegame ahead, where
Black's chances are not worse. For example,} Ne7 16. c3 Rc5 $1 17. Nxe7 Qxe7
18. Nc2 d5 19. Bf5 d4 $1 $132) (11. Bxb5 $5 axb5 12. Nxb5 {looks dangerous and
gave Black some problems in the distant past. However, 20 years ago, Peter
Leko demonstrated a reliable path for Black:} Ra4 13. b4 Rxb4 14. Nbc7+ Kd7 15.
O-O Rg8 $1 $132 16. g3 Rb7 17. Qh5 Qg5 18. Qxf7+ Be7 19. Nxe7 Nxe7 20. Ne6 Qg6
21. Nf8+ Rxf8 22. Qxf8 fxe4 23. Rfb1 Rc7 24. a4 e3 25. fxe3 Qe4 {0-1 (25)
Luther,T (2566)-Leko,P (2707) Essen 2002}) 11... Be6 12. O-O ({These days,
White often tries to get the upper hand with} 12. c3 Bg7 {and now: 1)} 13. Qh5
$5 {is quite popular.} ({2) GM Negi's old recommendation} 13. Nxb5 $5 axb5 14.
Bxb5 {leads to a double-edged position:} Rc8 15. Qa4 Bd7 16. exf5 O-O 17. O-O
e4 $1 $13 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gc6e5,Ge5d7,Gd7f6]}) 13... O-O 14. exf5 Bxd5 15. f6
e4 16. fxg7 Re8 17. Be2 {[%csl Yd4,Ye3,Ge4,Yf4] This position is roughly equal,
although I feel like White has a slightly easier game in this structure due to
his control of the dark-square complex.}) 12... Bxd5 13. exd5 {[#] A very
interesting middlegame. It seems like White should be better but Black's
dynamic possibilities compensate for his damaged pawn structure.} Ne7 14. Re1
$5 {[%csl Gf1,Rf5][%cal Gd3f1,Yg2g3,Yf1h3,Gc2c3,Ga3c2,Ya2a4] This positional
line has become the main attempt for White to obtain an advantage these days.}
({In the past, White preferred the more aggressive} 14. c3 Bg7 15. Qh5 e4 16.
Bc2 O-O 17. Rae1 {but Black was usually doing well in practice after} Qc8 $1
$13 {[%cal Gb5b4,Yc8f5]}) 14... Bg7 15. c3 O-O 16. Nc2 (16. Qh5 $5 {might be a
more accurate move order in order to provoke} e4 17. Bf1 Re8 18. Nc2 Nxd5 19.
Qxf5 Re5 20. Qh3 $11 {[%csl Yd4,Ye3] This structure is very similar to the
main line of 12.c3 Bg7 13.Qh5. Again, even though the position is roughly
equal, it feels a bit easier to play for White because of the central blockade.
} Qb6 21. Rad1 Rae8 22. Rxe4 Rxe4 23. Rxd5 R4e5) 16... f4 $5 {an ambitious
plan, very much in the spirit of the opening. Black is ready to give up his
queenside to speed up the kingside attack.} (16... Qd7 17. Bf1 {[%cal Gg2g3,
Yf1h3]}) 17. a4 f5 18. axb5 e4 $44) 11. Bd3 (11. c3 f5 (11... Ne7 $6 {is too
slow here in the view of} 12. Nc2 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 {[%csl Yd5,Yf5][%cal Gc2e3]
and Ne3 next.}) 12. Bd3 (12. exf5 {leads to a well-known Sveshnikov tabiya:}
Bxf5 13. Nc2 O-O 14. Nce3 (14. a4 {is premature. Black can exploit his lead in
development by tactical means:} Be6 $1 {[%csl Rd5]} 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Qxa8
17. Bxb5 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Rd5,Rg2]}) 14... Be6 15. Bd3 f5 {[#]} 16. O-O ({Another
big line goes} 16. Qh5 e4 17. Bc2 Ne7 18. Rd1 {and here Black gets nice
counterplay with a help of thematic pawn sacrifice} b4 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3][%cal
Yg7b2,Yc8c2]}) (16. Bc2 {Black can virtually force a draw with} f4 $5 17. Qh5
Rf7 $11 {[%csl Rd5,Re3][%cal Gg8f8] etc.}) 16... Kh8 17. Qh5 e4 18. Bc2 {
[%csl Yc2,Re4,Rf5,Rh7][%cal Gf2f3] White plans to undermine the e4-pawn and
attack the one on f5. We have two good ways to fight against it:} Ne7 {[%csl
Gd5][%cal Yg7e5]} ({and} 18... Ne5 $5 19. Nf4 Bd7 {which leads to more complex
play}) 19. Rad1 Nxd5 20. Nxd5 Be5 $132) 12... Ne7 $1 {This is much simpler and
in the spirit of the 10...Bg7 line} ({than} 12... Be6 {which gives White many
more interesting options, such as} 13. Qh5 $5 ({and} 13. Nxb5 $5 axb5 14. Bxb5
$44)) 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 {This transposes to the main line 11.Bd3 Ne7 12.Nxe7 Qxe7
with 13.c3}) (11. g3 $5 {has become popular recently. White doesn't mind us
playing 11...f5, which transposes into 10...f5 11.g3. However, we can follow
an independent path here with} Ne7 $5 (11... f5 12. Bg2 fxe4 13. Bxe4 Be6) 12.
Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Bg2 d5 $1 {The key idea. This pawn sacrifice promises good
compensation to Black.} 14. Qxd5 (14. exd5 $6 Qb4+ {[%csl Rb2,Re1]} 15. c3 Qxb2
) 14... Rb8 15. O-O O-O 16. Qd3 f5 $1 $44) 11... Ne7 12. Nxe7 (12. c4 Nxd5 13.
cxd5 f5 14. exf5 e4 15. Bxe4 Bxb2 16. Nc2 Bc3+ 17. Kf1 Qh4) 12... Qxe7 {[#]}
13. c4 {This is the most direct continuation. It leads to sharp play and the
opening theory runs deep, sometimes even into the endgame. Nevertheless, Black
should be in great shape if he knows his theory.} (13. c3 $5 {[%csl Rb5][%cal
Ga3c2,Ga2a4,Yc2b4,Yb4d5] is a more quiet, positional variation. However, it
should not be underestimated because White can usually put pressure on the
queenside. As Black, we must create counterplay on the kingside and the center
as quickly as possible.} f5 14. O-O (14. Nc2 Qb7 $1) (14. Qh5 d5 $1) 14... O-O
15. Nc2 Rb8 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ra2a4]} (15... d5 $5 {is a popular move in
correspondence chess.} 16. exf5 e4 17. Be2 Rd8 $13) (15... f4 16. a4 bxa4 17.
Rxa4 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf7f5] is quite double-edged.}) 16. exf5 e4 17. Be2 Bxf5
18. Nb4 Qg5 $132 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gf5h3,Gg7e5]}) 13... f5 14. O-O O-O 15. Qh5 {
The sharpest option.} (15. Qf3 {used to be the main line some time ago but it
has been neutralized in the meantime with} Qb7 $1 (15... d5 {is less appealing
in the view of} 16. cxd5 fxe4 17. Bxe4 Rb8 18. Rfd1 Qg5 19. d6 {[%csl Yd6]})
16. exf5 Qxf3 17. gxf3 e4 $1 18. Bxe4 d5 $3 {A fantastic concept. In the
arising endgame, Black gets sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawns
thanks to his powerful bishop pair.} 19. Bxd5 Rb8 $5 (19... Bxf5 20. Bxa8 Rxa8
$44)) 15... Rb8 (15... d5 $5 16. cxd5 Qd8 $1 {is Carlsen's favorite. Black
usually obtains a slightly worse but very drawish endgame after} 17. exf5 Qxd5
18. Rad1 e4 19. Bxb5 Qxf5 20. Qxf5 Bxf5 {[%csl Rb2] etc.}) 16. exf5 (16. Rae1
fxe4 17. Bxe4 f5 18. Bd5+ Kh8 {[%csl Ra3,Ye5,Yf5,Yg7] is already very good for
Black.}) 16... e4 17. Rae1 Bb7 {[%csl Ra3,Yb7,Yd6,Ye4,Yg7][%cal Yd6d5] This is
the main line. It's very double-edged, but Black has his fair share of chances,
thanks to the strong pawn center and the bishop pair.} 18. Qg4 (18. cxb5 d5 19.
bxa6 Ba8 $44) 18... Rfe8 $13 19. cxb5 (19. b3 Kh8) 19... Kh8 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,
Gg7e5,Yg8g1] The crucial idea allows Black to obtain strong counterplay on the
kingside.} (19... d5 {is slightly inferior, though still playable.} 20. bxa6
Ba8 21. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Re8g8]} Red8 22. Re3 Kh8 23. Rb3 Rg8) 20. bxa6
Ba8 21. a7 Rbd8 22. Nb5 d5 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gg7e5]} *

