1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 Ne7 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. c4 f5 14. O-O O-O
15. Qf3 {[#]} Qb7 $1 (15... d5 {used to be the main line for quite some time.}
16. cxd5 fxe4 17. Bxe4 Rb8 18. Rfd1 Qg5 19. d6 {[%csl Yd6] However, this type
of position is a little tricky for Black in practice.}) 16. exf5 Qxf3 17. gxf3
e4 $1 18. Bxe4 d5 $3 {A brilliant concept: Black gave away his entire pawn
center to open the position for his bishop pair.} 19. Bxd5 Bxf5 {The most
popular continuation.} ({However,} 19... Rb8 $5 {strikes me as a more
practical choice.} 20. Rad1 (20. Rab1 Bxf5 21. Be4 Bh3 22. Rfd1 Kh8 $1 23. Kh1
Rg8 $44) 20... Bxb2 21. Nc2 Bxf5 22. Ne3 Bh3 23. Rfe1 Bc3 24. Re2 Rfc8 $5 {
[%cal Rc4c5]} (24... Rfd8 25. c5 {is more tricky.}) 25. cxb5 Rxb5 26. Rc2 Rcc5
$11 {1/2-1/2 (44) Havumaki,A (2416)-Shulman,B (2411) ICCF email 2016}) 20. Bxa8
Rxa8 21. Rae1 Bd3 22. Re3 Bxf1 23. Kxf1 Bxb2 24. cxb5 axb5 25. Nxb5 Rxa2 26.
Re2 Ra1+ 27. Kg2 Bf6 $14 {[#] A very drawish endgame, similar to the one in
the Qh5 line. White can push without any risk for many moves here, though.} 28.
Nd6 Ra5 29. f4 Rd5 30. Re8+ Kg7 31. Ne4 Bd4 32. Kf3 f5 33. Ng3 Kf7 34. Rc8 Bf6
35. Rc6 Ra5 36. Kg2 Bh4 37. Ne2 Ra2 38. Kf1 Ra1+ 39. Nc1 Bf6 40. Kg2 Ra5 41.
Rc7+ Kg6 42. Rd7 Ra4 43. Kf3 Rd4 44. Rc7 Rd5 45. Ke2 Rb5 46. Nd3 Ra5 47. Kf3
Rd5 48. Nc5 h6 49. Ne6 Bh4 50. Nf8+ Kh5 51. Rf7 Rd3+ 52. Ke2 Rh3 53. f3 Rxh2+
54. Kd3 Be1 55. Rxf5+ Kh4 56. Re5 Bb4 57. Ne6 Kg3 58. Rb5 Bd6 59. f5 Kxf3 60.
f6 Kg4 61. Rd5 Ba3 62. f7 Rf2 63. Rd4+ Kg3 64. Rd7 Rf6 65. Ng7 Kg4 66. Ke4 h5
67. Ke5 Bb2+ 68. Kd5 Ba3 69. Ra7 Bf8 70. Ne6 Bh6 71. Kd6 h4 72. Ke7 Rf2 73. Ra8
h3 74. Rh8 Kh5 1/2-1/2

