1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 ({If White chooses a different move
order:} 11. c3 f5 12. Bd3 (12. exf5 Bxf5 {[%emt 0:00:04] -Game}) (12. Nxb5 $2 {
is premature because of} axb5 13. Bxb5 Bb7 $1 {If White wants to sacrifice a
piece on b5, he should do it when our bishop is one e6, so that Bb7 is not
possible.} 14. exf5 O-O 15. Qg4 Kh8 $19) {it is essential to remember that we
have} 12... Ne7 $1 {an important option that allows us to avoid the complex 12.
..Be6 line.} (12... Be6 {leads to positions from the 10...f5 line.} 13. Qh5 $5
(13. Nxb5 $5 axb5 14. Bxb5 $13)) {White has nothing better than} 13. Nxe7 Qxe7
{when we transpose into the main line.}) 11... Ne7 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. O-O (13.
c3 f5 14. Nc2 {[#] This is an attempt to save a tempo on 0-0 in order to
transfer the knight to d5 more quickly.} (14. Qh5 d5 $1 15. exf5 e4 16. O-O Qf6
17. Be2 b4 18. Nc2 bxc3 19. bxc3 Qxf5 20. Qxf5 Bxf5 $11) (14. O-O O-O {- main
line}) 14... Qb7 $5 {[%csl Re4,Rg2][%cal Yb7h1] This seems to be the most
principled way to exploit the downside of White's last move.} (14... O-O {
leads to more complex, although still playable position:} 15. Qh5 $5 (15. O-O {
-main line}) 15... f4 16. O-O-O $5 (16. O-O a5 $1 17. Bxb5 Rb8 18. a4 f5 $132)
16... Be6 17. g3 Bxa2 18. gxf4 Qf6 19. f5 Bh6+ 20. Ne3 Kh8 $11) 15. f3 {
[%cal Yb6g1,Yh4e1] keeps the center solid but weakens the dark squares.} (15.
exf5 Qxg2 16. Rf1 Bb7 $13 17. a4 O-O 18. Qh5 Qf3 19. Qxf3 Bxf3 $11) 15... f4
16. Nb4 O-O 17. O-O Be6 $11 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gf7f5,Ga6a5,Gb5b4]} 18. Rf2 {[#]} Bf6
$5 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf6d8,Gd8b6]} (18... a5 19. Nd5 f5 $11) 19. Rd2 Bd8 20. Bc2
Bb6+ 21. Kh1 Bc5 22. Nd5 Kh8 23. Qe1 Bxd5 24. Rxd5 Qe7 25. b4 Bb6 26. a4 bxa4
27. Rxa4 Rg8 28. Qf1 Qh4 $36 {1-0 (66) Schneider,D (2486)-Sevillano,E (2461)
Parsippany 2006}) 13... O-O 14. c3 f5 15. Nc2 {[#] The critical position of
this variation. Black needs to choose a plan. We have three reasonable options
at our disposal.} Rb8 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ra2a4] This is the most popular move
since it prevents a2-a4.} (15... d5 $5 {is the favorite move of correspondence
players.} 16. exf5 (16. exd5 e4 17. Re1 Rd8 18. Bf1 Bb7 $11 19. Ne3 $6 Qg5)
16... e4 17. Be2 Rd8 18. a4 (18. Nd4 Qf6 $1 19. a3 (19. g4 b4 $132) 19... Bxf5
20. Bg4 Bxg4 21. Qxg4 Qg6 $11) 18... bxa4 19. Rxa4 Bxf5 {[%csl Ra6,Gd5,Ge4]
[%cal Yc2e3,Yc2d4,Yc2b4] [#] The engine claims this position is roughly equal,
although I am not a big fan of this pawn structure for Black. I imagine White
having an easier game when our pawns are relatively static. Nevertheless,
Black has been doing fine in correspondence chess. It's crucial to combine the
attack on the backward b2-pawn with the d4-break.} 20. Qd2 (20. Rxa6 Rxa6 21.
Bxa6 Qd6 22. Be2 Qb6 $1 $44 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3][%cal Yg7b2]} 23. Qc1 Rb8 24. Nb4 d4
$132) (20. Nd4 Qf6 21. Bxa6 Qg6 $1 {[%cal Gf5h3]} 22. Nxf5 Qxf5 $44 {[%cal
Gd5d4]}) (20. Ne3 Qd7 21. Ra5 Be6 22. Bg4 Qb7 23. Bxe6 fxe6 24. Qe2 Rdb8 $132)
20... a5 21. Rfa1 Qc7 22. R4a3 Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rb2]} 23. Nd4 Bd7 24. b4 a4 25. b5
Qc5 26. Rxa4 Rxa4 27. Rxa4 Rc8 $132 {[%csl Rc3] 1/2-1/2 (36) Osipov,A (2382)
-Broniek,M (2398) LSS email 2017}) (15... f4 {[%csl Rg7] was Kasparov's choice
against Judit Polgar. It is a strategically risky approach since the bishop on
g7 will likely remain shut in for a long time.} 16. a4 bxa4 17. Rxa4 Qb7 $5 {
[%csl Rb2,Re4] is a completely unexpected yet effective approach.} ({It is
more usual for Black to try to attack on the kingside, for example:} 17... Kh8
18. Qh5 Bb7 19. Rfa1 {1-0 (37) Piorun,K (2640)-Markos,J (2559) Heraklion 2017}
Qc7 $1 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Ga6a5,Gf7f5]} 20. Bxa6 Bc6 21. Rb4 f5 $1 22. exf5 d5
$44) 18. Qa1 (18. Nb4 a5 19. Qa1 f3 $1 $132) 18... Bd7 19. Ra5 Bb5 20. Qd1 Qb6
21. Ra2 (21. b4 Qc6 $1 22. Na3 Qxc3 23. Nxb5 axb5 24. Bxb5 Rxa5 25. bxa5 Qxa5
$11) 21... a5 22. Bxb5 Qxb5 23. Na3 Qb7 {[%csl Rb2,Re4]} 24. Qd3 f5 $1 25. exf5
d5 26. Rd1 Rad8 27. Nc2 Qb6 $44 {1/2-1/2 (40) Karpanov,V (2257) -Robert,G 
(2329) ICCF email 2014}) 16. exf5 (16. Re1 fxe4 17. Bxe4 Kh8 18. Nb4 Qc7 19.
Nd5 Qd8 20. Qh5 f5 21. Bc2 Rb7 $3 22. Re3 e4 23. Rh3 Be5 24. f4 exf3 25. Rxf3
Rg7 $132) 16... e4 {One of the main positions in the 10. ... Bg7-line. White
has a better structure, but as usual, Black tries to use dynamic factors and
fight for activity.} 17. Be2 (17. Re1 Bxf5 18. Nb4 a5 19. Nd5 (19. Nc6 $2 Qb7
$17) 19... Qe5 20. Bc2 Bg6 $13) 17... Bxf5 18. Nb4 Qg5 $1 {[%cal Gf5h3] [#]}
19. Kh1 (19. f4 $5 {is the critical move these days.} exf3 20. Bxf3 Be5 $1 {
[%csl Ye5,Yf5,Rg1,Yg5] Black's activity compensates for his structural
weaknesses. However, it is essential to be precise in this double-edged
position.} 21. Nxa6 (21. Rf2 $5 Rbc8 22. g3 Bh3 23. Bg2 Be6 24. Nxa6 h5 $1 $44)
21... Rbc8 22. Qe2 $6 {[#]} Kh8 $1 23. Nb4 Rfe8 $2 (23... Rg8 $1 24. Nc6 Bf4
25. Bd5 Bh3 $40) 24. Qf2 Rc4 25. g3 Rh4 26. Rae1 (26. Bg2 $1 Rxh2 27. Kxh2 Rg8
28. Kg1 Bxg3 29. Qe2 $1 Bg4 30. Rf3 $1 Qc5+ 31. Kf1 Bh2 32. Ke1 Qg1+ 33. Qf1
$16) 26... Rg8 27. Nc6 Bxg3 28. hxg3 Rh3 29. g4 Bxg4 30. Qd4+ f6 31. Bg2 Bf3 {
0-1 (31) Brinck Claussen,B (2359)-Berczes,D (2450) Budapest 2006}) (19. Qxd6
Rbd8 20. Qg3 Qd2 $132) (19. Qc1 Qxc1 20. Raxc1 Ra8 21. Rfd1 Be6 $132) 19... Be5
$1 {[%csl Ye5]} 20. a4 (20. Nxa6 Rb6 21. Nb4 d5 $1 $40 {[%cal Gb6h6]}) 20... a5
$1 (20... bxa4 21. Rxa4 {[%csl Ra6]}) 21. Nc6 bxa4 22. f4 (22. Nxb8 Rxb8 {
Black's activity compensates for the slight loss of material.} 23. Qc2 a3 $1
24. bxa3 (24. Rxa3 e3 25. f4 (25. Qa4 Rxb2 26. f4 Bxf4 27. Qxf4 Qxf4 28. Rxf4
Rxe2 29. Kg1 (29. Ra1 Bd7 $17) 29... Be4 $17) 25... Bxf4 26. Qa4 Rxb2 $17)
24... Rc8 25. Qc1 Qh4 26. g3 Qf6 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Ye5][%cal Gd6d5,Gd5d4]}) 22...
exf3 23. Rxf3 Be4 24. Nxb8 Rxb8 $36 {Black achieved maximum activity and had a
better position.} 25. Rxa4 d5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] He would rather keep the Bishop
than take on f3!} 26. b4 Qh4 $2 {That's a pity - it spoils a very nice game by
this loss of time.} (26... Qh6 $1 27. h3 (27. Qg1 Bxf3 28. Bxf3 (28. gxf3+ $142
Kh8 $17) 28... Re8 $15) (27. g3 Bxc3 $17) 27... Bc7 $40 {[%cal Gh6d6]}) 27. g3
$1 (27. Qg1 Bxf3 28. Bxf3 Bxc3 $17 {[%cal Gb8e8,Ge8e1] /-+.} (28... Re8 29. g3)
29. g3 Qf6) 27... Qh6 (27... Bxg3 $2 28. Qg1 $1 {Probably Kramnik missed this.
Otherwise I cannot explain his 26th move.}) 28. Bd3 Bxf3+ (28... Bxg3 29. Ra2 {
[%cal Ga2g2]}) 29. Qxf3 {White consolidated and is out of danger.} Qc1+ 30. Kg2
Qd2+ 31. Qe2 Qxc3 32. Rxa5 Rxb4 33. Ra2 {A pawn up does not matter, so Black
decided to call it a day.} Rb2 34. Rxb2 1/2-1/2

