1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c3 f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Nc2 O-O 14. Nce3 (
14. a4 {is premature. Black can exploit his lead in development with the help
of a neat tactical idea:} Be6 $1 15. axb5 (15. g3 bxa4 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal
Ga8b8]}) 15... axb5 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. Bxb5 $2 {[#]} (17. Nc7 Qa7 $1 18. Nxe6 (
18. Qxd6 Bb3 19. Qxc6 Qa2 20. Ne3 Qb1+ 21. Ke2 e4 $40) 18... fxe6 $36 {[%csl
Rf2]}) (17. Nce3 Nd4 $1) 17... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Rd5,Rg2]} 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. cxd4
Qxg2 20. Rf1 (20. Bc6 e4 21. Rf1 Qg5 $17) 20... Qb7 21. d5 Bh3 $19 {0-1 (26)
Golubev,M (2461) -Zhigalko,S (2572) Chess.com INT 2022}) 14... Be6 15. Bd3 f5 {
[%csl Rh7][%cal Rf5f4,Yd5f4,Ye5e4,Gb5b4] [#] White has good control over the
central squares and it is not easy for Black to push his pawns forward.
Nevertheless, Black often achieves good counterplay by combining the central
tension with queenside play (think ...b5-b4 break!).} 16. O-O (16. Qh5 e4 17.
Bc2 Ne7 18. Rd1 {[#]} b4 $1 {A thematic pawn sacrifice to open the center for
our pieces.} 19. cxb4 (19. O-O bxc3 20. bxc3 Kh8 $11 {[%csl Rc3]} 21. g3 Rc8
22. Bb3 Bf7 23. Qe2 Bxd5 24. Nxd5 Nxd5 25. Bxd5 a5 26. c4 Rb8 {1/2-1/2 (26)
Ponomariov,R (2684) -Leko,P (2739) Yerevan 2001}) 19... Rc8 $1 {[%csl Gc2]} 20.
Bb3 Ng6 $1 {[%csl Rb3]} 21. O-O Kh8 $36 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 22. f4 $2 exf3 23. Qxf3
f4 24. Nc4 Qg5 25. Nxd6 Bg4 $19 {0-1 (65) Zeng,C (2597)-Lenic,L (2627) Chess.
com INT 2021}) (16. Bc2 f4 {This leads to a well-known draw by force.} ({
Black can also keep the tension with} 16... Kh8 $5 17. Qh5 e4 $13 {[%cal Gc6e7]
}) 17. Qh5 Rf7 18. Bxh7+ Kf8 19. Bf5 Qe8 $1 20. Qg4 Bxf5 21. Nxf5 Qe6 22. Nfe3
Qh6 23. Nf5 Qe6 $11) (16. a4 b4 $1) 16... Kh8 $5 {A useful waiting move.} (
16... e4 {is probably premature. It is better to wait with this advance until
White goes Qh5.} 17. Nf4 Bf7 18. Bc2 Be5 19. Nfd5 $1 {[%csl Rf5,Rf7][%cal
Gf2f4]} Kh8 {[#]} 20. f4 exf3 21. Qxf3 {[%csl Rf5] This is the kind of
position you usually want to avoid with black pieces in this variation.} Bxd5
22. Nxd5 Qh4 23. g3 Rg8 24. Nf4 $16 {0-1 (28) Topalov,V (2740)-Carlsen,M (2861)
Abidjan 2019}) 17. Qh5 (17. a4 {[#]} b4 $1 18. cxb4 e4 19. Nf4 Nd4 $1 {[%csl
Rb4,Yd4]} 20. Nxe6 Nxe6 21. Bc4 Nd4 $15 {[%csl Yd4]}) (17. Bc2 Ne7 18. Bb3 f4
$40) 17... e4 18. Bc2 (18. Nf4 $4 {is not possible now due to} Bf7 {[%csl Rh5]}
) 18... Ne7 {This is the most solid approach.} (18... Ne5 $5 $13 {leads to a
more complex fight.} 19. Nf4 (19. Rad1 Bf7 20. Qh3 Qg5 21. Qg3 Bh6 22. Qxg5
Bxg5 $132) 19... Bd7 {[%csl Yf5]} 20. Ned5 b4 $1 $146 {This thematic pawn
sacrifice often works well for Black.} 21. cxb4 (21. c4 a5 $13) 21... Be8 22.
Qh3 Bf7 23. Bb3 Qg5 $44) 19. Rad1 (19. Nf4 Bf7 $132 {[%cal Gg7e5,Gd6d5]}) 19...
Nxd5 (19... Rc8 20. f3 Bf7 21. Qh3 Nxd5 22. Nxd5) 20. Nxd5 Be5 {[%csl Ye5]
White cannot easily challenge this powerful bishop.} 21. f3 {[#]} ({In the
event of} 21. f4 {we can retreat} Bg7 $1 {[%csl Ye4,Yf5][%cal Gb5b4,Ga6a5] and
focus on the queenside counterplay now that White cannot undermine the center
with f2-f3 anymore.} 22. Kh1 (22. g4 b4 $1 23. Nxb4 d5 $17 {[%csl Rb4][%cal
Gd5d4]}) 22... a5 23. a3 Rc8 (23... b4 $5 24. axb4 axb4 25. Nxb4 Qb6 $44 {
[%csl Rb2]}) 24. Qh3 Rc5 $4 (24... Qe8 25. Bb3 b4 $1 26. axb4 a4 27. Ba2 a3 28.
bxa3 Bxd5 29. Bxd5 Rxc3 30. Qh4 Rxa3 $11) 25. Bxe4 $16 {1-0 (33) Zeng,C (2597)
-Mamedov,R (2654) Chess.com INT 2021}) 21... b4 $1 22. fxe4 bxc3 23. bxc3 f4
$44 {[%csl Rc2,Ye5] [#] Black has a typical positional compensation thanks to
the blockade on the dark squares. Interestingly, White collapsed on the very
next move in the game.} 24. Qh6 $4 Bg4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ye5g7]} 25. h3 Bg7 $19
26. Qxg7+ Kxg7 27. hxg4 Qg5 28. Rd3 Rab8 29. Bb3 Rbe8 30. Rd4 Qxg4 31. Rf3 Kh8
32. Kf1 Re5 33. Bd1 Rh5 34. Kg1 Qh4 35. Rf1 Qh2+ 36. Kf2 Qg3+ 37. Kg1 Rh2 38.
Rd2 Qh4 {0-1 (38) Olsson,A (2327) -Eklund,L (2300) Sweden 2002 EXT 2004 [dkulj]
} 0-1

