1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 f5 11. Bxb5 {One can't help admiring Thomas
courage to sac a piece against one of the strongest theoreticians in the world.
White's decision seems like an experiment: probably Thomas was willing to
check Leko's analysis in this sharpest line of Sveshnikov Sicilian. Well,
Peter confirmed his status once again...} axb5 12. Nxb5 Ra4 13. b4 {After
Shirov's loss against Kasparov earlier this year I thought 13.b4 will take a
rest for a while. On the other hand this was based rather on subjective
thinking since the result of that game wasn't necessarily a direct consequence
of the opening outcome.} Rxb4 {Luther must have had an improvement over
Shirov-Kasparov. Unless he was willing to force a draw, which frankly speaking,
I doubt.} (13... Qh4 14. O-O Rg8 15. f4 (15. c3 f4 16. Qxa4 Rxg2+ {was a draw
in Luther-McShane, Lippstadt 2000. I guess Thomas would have rather go for 15
f4, trying to improve Shirov's play.}) 15... Kd8 16. c3 (16. Nb6 $5 {The most
serious attempt to improve on Shirov's play.} Rxb4 17. Nxc8 Kxc8 18. Qd5 $13)
16... Ra6 17. a4 $6 fxe4 18. f5 $6 {After this Black is certainly much better.
However, it makes sense to give the whole game, as in the end the cause for
White's loss was the same as in our main game: the diagonal a8-h1.} (18. Ndc7 {
and the fight is far from being over yet.} Qh3 19. Qc2 Rb6 20. Kh1 $1 Qh4 (
20... Qd3 21. Qa2 $1) (20... Qg4 21. Nd5 {[%cal Gd5f6]}) 21. a5 Rb7 22. a6 Rxc7
23. Nxc7 Kxc7 24. a7 Bb7 25. a8=Q Bxa8 26. Rxa8 $13) 18... Bb7 19. Ra2 e3 20.
Nxe3 Qe4 21. Re1 Nxb4 22. cxb4 Bh6 23. Kh1 Bxe3 24. Qe2 Rc6 25. a5 Qxb4 26.
Nxd6 Rxd6 27. Qxe3 Qd4 28. Qc1 Qd5 {0-1 Shirov,A-Kasparov,G/Linares 2002}) 14.
Nbc7+ Kd7 15. O-O Rg8 $1 {A strong flexible continuation, which is not a
novelty, though. ...Rg8 can be considered a universal move in 11.Bxb5 line. As
we'll see, Black would better keep the queen on d8 for a while (unlike in
Luther-Reinderman).} (15... Qg5 16. Nxb4 Nxb4 17. c3 {The queen's absence from
the queenside makes Black's king vulnerable.} Kxc7 18. cxb4 fxe4 19. Qa4 {
with attack, Luther,T-Reinderman,D/Venlo 2000. Note that white queen went to
the side opposite to Black queen.}) (15... Rb7 16. Qh5 $1 {Again black queen
cannot take countermeasures against her white colleague.} Ne7 17. Qxf7 Kc6 18.
Rab1 fxe4 19. Rxb7 Kxb7 20. Rb1+ Kc6 21. Rb6+ Kc5 22. Rb3 {and White won,
Shirov,A-Lautier,J/Monte Carlo 2000.}) 16. g3 (16. Nxb4 Nxb4 17. Nd5 (17. c3 {
Compared to Luther-Reinderman, this fails to impress the black queen on d8.}
Qxc7 18. cxb4 fxe4 {is also good for Black.}) 17... Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Ke7 19. Rab1
Be6 20. Qb7+ Kf6 21. exf5 Bxf5 22. f4 e4 23. Qd5 Qc8 24. Rb5 Qe6 25. Qd4+ Kg6
26. Qe3 (26. g4 Kh6 $1) 26... h6 $17 {Baer,H-Berriot,B/Latin Am-Cup4 corr 1987}
) (16. Qh5 Qg5 $1) 16... Rb7 $1 {Now Black plays like in the game
Shirov-Lautier. Including the moves g3 and ...Rg8 favours Black.} 17. Qh5 Qg5
$1 {That's the difference to Shirov-Lautier. The queen gets out. The next part
of the game proves that White cannot create anything real.} 18. Qxf7+ Be7 19.
Nxe7 Nxe7 20. Ne6 ({After} 20. Nd5 {Black has a pleasant choice between 20...
Kd8 or 20...Qg7, in both cases with a position close to winning for Black.})
20... Qg6 21. Nf8+ Rxf8 22. Qxf8 fxe4 23. Rfb1 Rc7 $19 24. a4 e3 25. fxe3 Qe4 {
Just like in Shirov-Kasparov, the weakness of the long diagonal is fatal for
White. Another serious blow in this variation.} 0-1

